{"title_page": "Rinat Yisrael", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n[[File:Amram Aburbeh Rinat Israel siddur Ha'Sfaradim ve'Edot HaMizrach.jpg||thumb|right|Title page of ''Siddur Rinat Yisrael Nusach HaSfaradim and Edot HaMizrach''.]]\n[[File:IDF_soldier_put_on_tefillin.jpg||thumb|right|Israeli Soldier praying from a ''Siddur Rinat Yisrael''.]]\n'''Rinat Yisrael''' is a family of [[siddur]]im (prayer books), popular within the [[Religious Zionist]] (and [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox]]) communities in [[Israel]], and used by some in the [[Jewish diaspora|Diaspora]]; They are available in [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] only. \nThe siddur was first published in 1970 by the [[Moreshet Publishing Company]], and edited by Dr. [[Shlomo Tal]]. \n\nPublished in connection with the [[Israeli Ministry of Education]], the siddur aims to allow youngsters and students to become familiar and comfortable with the siddur and [[Jewish services|prayer service]]. To further this goal, Rinat Yisrael uses a large [[typeface]], a modern, easy to read [[font]], and uses special symbols to denote which syllable a word is accented on. Also included are references to verses quoted from the [[Tanakh]], and translations of difficult words, including passages in [[Aramaic]], into [[modern Hebrew]]. Additionally, most passages are printed in the same size type, in order not to lend the impression that some prayers are more important than others.\n\nNew prayers recognizing the rebirth of the State of [[Israel]] have been added, including a [[Prayer for the Welfare of the State of Israel]], a Prayer for the Soldiers of The [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]], and a service for [[Israel Independence Day]].\n\nRinat Yisrael has been published in three different versions, or ''[[Nusach|Nuschaot]]'': [[Nusach Ashkenaz|Ashkenaz]] (published in both Israel and Diaspora versions), [[Nusach Sefard|Sefard]], and [[Sephardic]] / [[Edot HaMizrach]]. Rabbi [[Amram Aburbeh]] the latter.  The siddurim are published in various sizes.\n\nAlong with the siddur, other publications in the Rinat Yisrael series include [[machzor]]im for [[Rosh Hashanah]], [[Yom Kippur]], [[Sukkot]], [[Pesach]], and [[Shavuot]]; a [[haggadah]]; a book of [[selichot]], and a book of ''[[kinnot]]'' for [[Tisha B'av]]. These are all produced in different versions, as the prayer book above.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Koren Siddur]]\n\n[[Category:Siddur versions]]\n[[Category:Religious_Zionism]]\n[[Category:1970 non-fiction books]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}\n[[File:Amram Aburbeh Rinat Israel siddur Ha'Sfaradim ve'Edot HaMizrach.jpg||thumb|right|Title page of ''Siddur Rinat Yisrael Nusach HaSfaradim and Edot HaMizrach''.]]\n[[File:IDF_soldier_put_on_tefillin.jpg||thumb|right|Israeli Soldier praying from a ''Siddur Rinat Yisrael''.]]\n'''Rinat Yisrael''' is a family of [[siddur]]im (prayer books), popular within the [[Religious Zionist]] (and [[Modern Orthodox Judaism|Modern Orthodox]]) communities in [[Israel]], and used by some in the [[Jewish diaspora|Diaspora]]; They are available in [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] only. \nThe siddur was first published in 1970 by the [[Moreshet Publishing Company]], and edited by Dr. [[Shlomo Tal]]. \n\nPublished in connection with the [[Israeli Ministry of Education]], the siddur aims to allow youngsters and students to become familiar and comfortable with the siddur and [[Jewish services|prayer service]]. To further this goal, Rinat Yisrael uses a large [[typeface]], a modern, easy to read [[font]], and uses special symbols to denote which syllable a word is accented on. Also included are references to verses quoted from the [[Tanakh]], and translations of difficult words, including passages in [[Aramaic]], into [[modern Hebrew]]. Additionally, most passages are printed in the same size type, in order not to lend the impression that some prayers are more important than others.\n\nNew prayers recognizing the rebirth of the State of [[Israel]] have been added, including a [[Prayer for the Welfare of the State of Israel]], a Prayer for the Soldiers of The [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]], and a service for [[Israel Independence Day]].\n\nRinat Yisrael has been published in three different versions, or ''[[Nusach|Nuschaot]]'': [[Nusach Ashkenaz|Ashkenaz]] (published in both Israel and Diaspora versions), [[Nusach Sefard|Sefard]], and [[Sephardic]] / [[Edot HaMizrach]]. Rabbi [[Amram Aburbeh]] the latter.  The siddurim are published in various sizes.\n\nAlong with the siddur, other publications in the Rinat Yisrael series include [[machzor]]im for [[Rosh Hashanah]], [[Yom Kippur]], [[Sukkot]], [[Pesach]], and [[Shavuot]]; a [[haggadah]]; a book of [[selichot]], and a book of ''[[kinnot]]'' for [[Tisha B'av]]. These are all produced in different versions, as the prayer book above.\n\n==See also==\n[[Koren Siddur]]\n\n[[Category:Siddur versions]]\n[[Category:Religious_Zionism]]\n[[Category:1970 non-fiction books]]\n", "name_user": "Fintor", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rinat_Yisrael"}
{"title_page": "From Russia with Love (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1963 film in the James Bond series directed by Terence Young}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = From Russia with Love\n| image          = From Russia with Love \u2013 UK cinema poster.jpg\n| border         = yes\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster by [[Renato Fratini]] and [[Eric Pulford]]\n| alt            = The upper centre of the poster reads \"Meet James Bond, secret agent 007. His new incredible women&nbsp;... His new incredible enemies&nbsp;... His new incredible adventures&nbsp;...\" To the right is Bond holding a gun, to the left a montage of women, fights, and an explosion. On the bottom of the poster are the credits.\n| starring       = [[Sean Connery]]<br />[[Pedro Armend\u00e1riz]]<br />[[Lotte Lenya]]<br />[[Robert Shaw (British actor)|Robert Shaw]]<br />[[Bernard Lee]]<br />[[Daniela Bianchi]]\n| screenplay     = [[Richard Maibaum]]\n| story          = [[Johanna Harwood]]\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[From Russia, with Love (novel)|From Russia, with Love]]''|[[Ian Fleming]]}}\n| cinematography = [[Ted Moore]]\n| director       = [[Terence Young (director)|Terence Young]]\n| producer       = [[Harry Saltzman]]<br />[[Albert R. Broccoli]]\n| music          = [[John Barry (composer)|John Barry]]\n| editing        = [[Peter R. Hunt]]\n| studio         = [[Eon Productions]]\n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1963|10|10|London, premiere|1963|10|11|United Kingdom|1964|4|8|United States}}\n| runtime        = 115 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom<br />United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $2 million\n| gross          = $79 million\n}}\n'''''From Russia with Love''''' is a 1963 [[spy film]] and the second in the [[List of James Bond films|''James Bond'' series]] produced by [[Eon Productions]], as well as [[Sean Connery]]'s second role as [[MI6]] agent [[James Bond]]. It was directed by [[Terence Young (director)|Terence Young]], produced by [[Albert R. Broccoli]] and [[Harry Saltzman]], and written by [[Richard Maibaum]] and [[Johanna Harwood]], based on [[Ian Fleming]]'s [[From Russia, with Love (novel)|similarly named 1957 novel]]. In the film, Bond is sent to assist in the defection of Soviet [[consulate]] clerk [[Tatiana Romanova]] in [[Turkey]], where [[SPECTRE]] plans to avenge Bond's killing of [[Julius No|Dr. No]].\n\nFollowing the success of ''[[Dr. No (film)|Dr. No]]'', [[United Artists]] greenlit a sequel and doubled the budget available for the producers. In addition to filming on location in Turkey, the action scenes were shot at [[Pinewood Studios]], [[Buckinghamshire]], and in [[Scotland]]. Production ran over budget and schedule, and was rushed to finish by its scheduled October 1963 release date.\n\n''From Russia with Love'' was a critical and commercial success. It took in more than $78 million in worldwide box-office receipts, far more than its $2 million budget and more than its predecessor ''Dr. No'', thereby becoming a [[blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbuster]] in 1960s cinema.\n\nThis film also marked the debut of [[Desmond Llewelyn]] as [[Q (James Bond)|Q]], a role he would play for 36 years (and seventeen films) until ''[[The World Is Not Enough]]'' in 1999.\n\n== Plot ==\nSeeking revenge against [[Secret Intelligence Service|MI6]] Agent 007 [[James Bond]] for the death of their agent [[Julius No|Dr. No]] in [[Jamaica]],{{refn|name=Timeline|group=N|As depicted in the 1962 film ''[[Dr. No (film)|Dr. No]]''.}} international criminal organisation [[SPECTRE]] begins training agents to kill him. Irish assassin Donald \"Red\" Grant proves himself by quickly killing a fake Bond with a [[garrote]] concealed in his wristwatch during training.\n\nSPECTRE's chief planner, [[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic|Czech]] chess [[Grandmaster (chess)|grandmaster]] Kronsteen (Number 5), devises a plan to play British and Soviet intelligence against each other to procure a Lektor [[cryptography]] device from the [[Soviet Union|Soviets]] and lure Bond to his assassination. SPECTRE's chief executive [[Ernst Stavro Blofeld|(Number 1)]] puts [[Rosa Klebb]] (Number 3), a former [[SMERSH]] (Soviet counter-intelligence) colonel, in charge of the mission. Klebb chooses Grant to protect Bond until he acquires the Lektor, then eliminate 007 and steal the machine for SPECTRE (to be eventually sold back to its legitimate owner). Klebb also recruits [[Tatiana Romanova]], a cipher clerk at the Soviet consulate in [[Istanbul]], who believes Klebb is still working for SMERSH.\n\nIn [[London]], [[M (James Bond)|M]] informs Bond that Romanova has contacted \"Station T\" in Turkey, offering to defect with a top-secret Lektor on the condition that Bond handle her case personally. M decides the chance of obtaining a Lektor is worth the risk, and [[Q (James Bond)|Q]] gives Bond an [[Briefcase|attach\u00e9 case]] with concealed throwing knife, gold sovereigns, a [[tear gas]] booby trap, and an [[ArmaLite AR-7]] sniper rifle.\n\nIn Istanbul, Bond meets station head [[List of James Bond allies#Film allies|Ali Kerim Bey]], tailed by [[People's Republic of Bulgaria|Bulgarian]] agents working for Russia, who are, in turn, tailed by Grant; he kills one agent and dumps their car outside the Soviet Consulate. The Soviets bomb Kerim's office with a [[limpet mine]], but he is away from his desk with his mistress. He and Bond spy on a Soviet consulate meeting through a periscope in the aqueducts beneath Istanbul, and learn that Soviet agent Krilencu is responsible for the bombing. Kerim and Bond lay low at a rural [[Romani people|gypsy]] settlement, where Krilencu attacks them with a band of Bulgarians; Bond is saved by a sniper shot from Grant. Bond and Kerim track down Krilencu, and Kerim kills him with Bond's rifle.\n\nBond finds Romanova in his hotel suite and they have sex, neither aware SPECTRE is filming them. Romanova brings the consulate floor plans to the Ayasofya M\u00fczesi, formally the [[Hagia Sophia]], and Grant kills the other Bulgarian to ensure Bond receives them. Using the plans, Bond and Kerim steal the Lektor and escape with Romanova aboard the ''[[Orient Express]]''. Kerim and Bond subdue a Soviet security officer named Benz tailing them. Grant kills Kerim and Benz, preventing Bond from rendezvousing with one of Kerim's men.\n\nAt the [[Belgrade]] station, Bond passes word of Kerim Bey's death to his son, and asks for an agent from [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Station Y]] to meet him at [[Zagreb]]. Grant kills Nash, sent from Station Y, and poses as the agent. After drugging Romanova at dinner, Grant overpowers Bond, taunting him that Romanova believed she was working for Mother Russia, and reveals his plan to leave the compromising film of Bond and Romanova with a blackmail letter, staging their deaths as a murder-suicide to scandalise the British intelligence community. Bond tricks Grant into setting off the booby trap in his attach\u00e9 case and stabs him with the concealed knife before strangling him with his own garrote, and flees with Romanova in Grant's getaway truck.\n\nNumber 1 confronts Klebb and Kronsteen for their failure. Kronsteen is executed by the henchman Morzeny's poison-tipped switchblade in his shoe, while Klebb is given one last chance to acquire the Lektor, which they have arranged to sell back to the Russians.\n\nFollowing Grant's escape route, Bond destroys a SPECTRE helicopter, and he and Romanova steal Grant's boat on the [[Dalmatia]]n coast. Pursued by Morzeny's squadron of SPECTRE powerboats, Bond detonates his own powerboat's fuel drums with a [[flare gun]], engulfing the pursuers in a sea of flames.\n\nHe and Romanova reach a hotel in [[Venice]], where they are attacked by Klebb, disguised as a maid. She tries to kick Bond with a poisoned switchblade shoe, but Romanova shoots her. Their mission accomplished, Bond and Romanova depart on a romantic boat ride, and Bond throws Grant's blackmail film into the canal.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Sean Connery]] as [[Portrayal of James Bond in film|James Bond]], [[Secret Intelligence Service|MI6]] agent 007.\n* [[Pedro Armend\u00e1riz]] as [[List of James Bond allies#Film-specific allies|Ali Kerim Bey]], head of MI6 Station T in Istanbul.\n* [[Lotte Lenya]] as [[Rosa Klebb|Rosa Klebb (SPECTRE No. 3)]], a former [[SMERSH (James Bond)|SMERSH]] colonel-turned-SPECTRE operative.\n* [[Robert Shaw (actor)|Robert Shaw]] as Donald \"Red\" Grant, a cunning SPECTRE assassin and one of the principal Bond enemies.\n* [[Daniela Bianchi]] as [[Tatiana Romanova]], a Soviet Consulate clerk and Bond's love interest. Fleming based Romanova on [[Krystyna Skarbek|Christine Granville]].<ref>''FILMFAX Magazine''. October 2003 \u2013 January 2004.</ref>\n**Bianchi's dialogue was dubbed by an uncredited [[Barbara Jefford]].<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite AV media notes|title=From Russia with Love Ultimate Edition DVD|others=[[Terence Young (director)|Terence Young]]|origyear=1962|publisher=MGM Home Entertainment|year=2006|id=Accessed 30 December 2007}}</ref> \n* [[Bernard Lee]] as [[M (James Bond)|M]], chief of British Intelligence.\n* [[Walter Gotell]] as Morzeny, a SPECTRE thug who trains personnel on SPECTRE Island. Gotell would go on to play a different character, [[List of James Bond allies#General Gogol|General Gogol]], in later entries in the series.\n* [[Vladek Sheybal]] as Kronsteen (SPECTRE No. 5), a [[Czechoslovakia|Czechoslovak]] chess [[Grandmaster (chess)|grandmaster]] and SPECTRE agent.\n*[[Anthony Dawson]] as [[Ernst Stavro Blofeld|Ernst Stavro Blofeld (SPECTRE No. 1)]], the head and mastermind of SPECTRE and Bond's nemesis. Dawson previously played Professor Dent in [[Dr. No (film)|''Dr. No'']]. He was credited [[Pseudonym|pseudonymously]] as \"?\" for the role.\n**Dawson's dialogue was dubbed by an uncredited [[Eric Pohlmann]].\n* [[Lois Maxwell]] as [[Miss Moneypenny]], M's secretary.\n* [[Desmond Llewelyn]] as [[Q (James Bond)|Major Boothroyd]], head of MI6 [[Q (James Bond)|Q Branch]], also called the \"Equipment Officer\"\n* [[Eunice Gayson]] as [[Eunice Gayson#Bond films|Sylvia Trench]], Bond's semi-regular girlfriend.\n**Gayson's dialogue was dubbed by an uncredited [[Nikki van der Zyl]].\n* [[Francis de Wolff]] as Vavra, chief of a Gypsy tribe used for dirty work by Kerim Bey.\n*Fred Haggerty as Krilencu, a Bulgarian assassin who works as a killer for the Soviets in the [[Balkans]].\n*[[Aliza Gur]] and [[Martine Beswick]] as Vida (in green) and Zora (in red), respectively, two jealous Gypsy girls who are disputing the same man.\n\nAdditional cast members include [[Peter Bayliss]] as Russian agent Commissar Benz, [[Peter Madden (actor)|Peter Madden]] as British chessmaster MacAdams, [[George Pastell]] as the [[Orient Express]] train conductor, [[Nadja Regin]] as Kerim Bey's lonely girlfriend, Nusret Ataer as Mehmet, Kerim Bey's son and agent, Neville Jason as Kerim Bey's chauffeur, [[Michael Culver]] and [[Elizabeth Counsell]] as a couple in a punt, William Hill as Captain Nash, a British agent killed and impersonated by Red Grant, and Lisa Guiraut as a Gypsy belly dancer.\n\n==Production==\nFollowing the financial success of ''Dr. No'', [[United Artists]] greenlit a second James Bond film. The studio doubled the budget offered to [[Eon Productions]] with $2 million, and also approved a bonus for Sean Connery, who would receive $100,000 along with his $54,000 salary.<ref>{{cite book|title=United Artists: the company that changed the film industry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9EeK5s3aw44C&pg=PA260|first=Tino|last=Balio|page=260|publisher=[[University of Wisconsin]] Press|year=1987|isbn=9780299230135}}</ref> As [[John F. Kennedy|President John F. Kennedy]] had named Fleming's novel ''[[From Russia, with Love (novel)|From Russia with Love]]'' among his ten favourite books of all time in [[Life (magazine)|''Life'']] magazine,<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> producers Broccoli and Saltzman chose this as the follow-up to Bond's cinematic debut in ''[[Dr. No (film)|Dr. No]]''. ''From Russia with Love'' was the last film President Kennedy saw at the White House on 20 November 1963 before going to Dallas.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.prospect.org/cs/articles?article=arthur_m_schlesinger_jr_19172007 |title=Arthur M. Schlesinger, Jr., 1917\u20132007  |journal=The American Prospect |date=17 September 2010 |accessdate=21 September 2010}}</ref> Most of the crew from the first film returned, with major exceptions being production designer [[Ken Adam]], who went to work on ''[[Dr. Strangelove]]'' and was replaced by ''Dr. No''{{'}}s art director [[Syd Cain]]; title designer [[Maurice Binder]] was replaced by [[Robert Brownjohn]], and stunt coordinator [[Bob Simmons (stunt man)|Bob Simmons]] was unavailable and was replaced by Peter Perkins<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> though Simmons performed stunts in the film.<ref>Brosnan, John ''James Bond in the Cinema'' Tantivy Press; 2nd edition (1981)</ref> [[John Barry (composer)|John Barry]] replaced [[Monty Norman]] as composer of the soundtrack.\n\nThe film introduced several conventions which would become essential elements of the series: a [[pre-title sequence]], the Blofeld character (referred to in the film only as \"Number 1\") (though Blofeld is mentioned in the end credits, with the actor referred to only as \"?\"), a secret-weapon gadget for Bond, a helicopter sequence (repeated in every subsequent Bond film except ''[[The Man with the Golden Gun (film)|The Man with the Golden Gun]]''), a postscript action scene after the main climax, a theme song with lyrics, and the line \"James Bond will return/be back\" in the credits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://whatculture.com/film/james-bond-retrospective-from-russia-with-love-1963|title=James Bond Retrospective: From Russia With Love (1963)|publisher=Whatculture|accessdate=22 September 2016|date=30 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Writing===\n[[Ian Fleming]]'s novel was a [[Cold War]] thriller but the producers replaced the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] undercover agency [[SMERSH]] with the crime syndicate SPECTRE so as to avoid controversial political overtones.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> The SPECTRE training grounds were inspired by the film ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]''.<ref name=\"young\"/> The original screenwriter was [[Len Deighton]], who accompanied Harry Saltzman, Syd Cain, and Terence Young to Istanbul<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hmssweblog.wordpress.com/2012/11/04/len-deighton-on-from-russia-with-love/ |title=Len Deighton on From Russia With Love &#124; The Spy Command |publisher=Hmssweblog.wordpress.com |date= 5 November 2012|accessdate=2016-09-30}}</ref> but he was replaced because of a lack of progress.<ref name=maibaum>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sWewbX79ISsC&pg=PA284|title=Backstory: interviews with screenwriters of Hollywood's golden age|author=McGilligan, Patrick|page=284|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|year=1986|isbn=978-0-520-05689-3|author-link=Patrick McGilligan (biographer)}}</ref> Thus, two of ''Dr. No''{{'}}s writers, [[Johanna Harwood]] and [[Richard Maibaum]], returned for the second film in the series.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> Some sources state Harwood was credited for the \"adaptation\" mostly for her suggestions which were carried over into Maibaum's script.<ref name=maibaum/> Harwood stated in an interview for ''Cinema Retro'' that she had been a screenwriter of several of Harry Saltzman's projects, and her screenplay for ''From Russia with Love'' had followed Fleming's novel closely, but she left the series due to what she called Terence Young's constant rewriting of her screenplay with ideas that were not in the original Fleming work.<ref>''Johanna Harwood Interview'' ''Movie Classics # 4'' Solo Publishing 2012</ref>\nMaibaum kept on making rewrites as filming progressed. Red Grant was added to the Istanbul scenes just prior to the film crew's trip to Turkey; this brought more focus to the SPECTRE plot, as Grant started saving Bond's life there (a late change during shooting involved Grant killing the bespectacled spy at Hagia Sophia instead of Bond, who ends up just finding the man dead).<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> For the last quarter of the movie, Maibaum added two chase scenes, with a helicopter and speedboats, and changed the location of Bond and Klebb's battle from Paris to Venice.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Chapman |first=James |year=2007 |title= Licence to Thrill |publisher= Cinema and Society |location= London/New York City |isbn=978-1-84511-515-9}}</ref> Uncredited rewrites were contributed by [[Berkely Mather]].\n\n===Casting===\nAlthough uncredited, the actor who played Number&nbsp;1 was [[Anthony Dawson]], who had played Professor Dent in the previous Bond film, ''Dr. No'', and appeared in several of Terence Young's films. In the end credits, Blofeld is credited with a [[question mark]]. Blofeld's lines were redubbed by Viennese actor [[Eric Pohlmann]] in the final cut.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> [[Peter Burton]] was unavailable to return as Major Boothroyd, so [[Desmond Llewelyn]], a Welsh actor who was a fan of the [[James Bond (comic strip)|Bond comic strip]] published in the ''[[Daily Express]]'', accepted the part. However, screen credit for Llewelyn was omitted at the opening of the film and is reserved for the exit credits, where he is credited simply as \"Boothroyd\". Llewelyn's character is not referred to by this name in dialogue, but M does introduce him as being from Q Branch. Llewelyn remained as the character, better known as Q, in all but one of the series' films until his death in 1999.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BikCz7XZijEC&pg=PA83|title=The rough guide to James Bond|first=Paul|last=Simpson|page=83|publisher=[[Rough Guides]]|year=2002|accessdate=25 March 2011|isbn=9781843531425}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Inside Q's Lab |medium=DVD |publisher=[[Metro Goldwyn Mayer|MGM]]/[[United Artists|UA]] Home Entertainment Inc |location=''On Her Majesty's Secret Service'' Ultimate Edition, Disk 2}}</ref>\n\nSeveral actresses were considered for the role of Tatiana, including Italians [[Sylva Koscina]] and [[Virna Lisi]], Danish actress [[Annette Stroyberg|Annette Vadim]], and English-born [[Tania Mallet]].<ref name=\"inside-frwl\">{{Cite AV media |title=Inside From Russia with Love |medium=DVD |publisher=[[Metro Goldwyn Mayer|MGM]]/[[United Artists|UA]] Home Entertainment Inc |year=2000}}</ref> [[Miss Universe 1960|1960]] [[Miss Universe]] runner-up Daniela Bianchi was ultimately cast, supposedly Sean Connery's choice. Bianchi started taking English classes for the role, but the producers ultimately chose to have her lines redubbed by British stage actress [[Barbara Jefford]] in the final cut.<ref name=\"commentary\">''From Russia with Love'' [[audio commentary]], Ultimate Edition DVD</ref> The scene in which Bond finds Tatiana in his hotel bed was used for Bianchi's [[screen test]], with Dawson standing in, this time, as Bond.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> The scene later became the traditional screen test scene for prospective James Bond actors and Bond Girls.<ref>{{Cite AV media |year=2000 | title = Inside Octopussy | medium = DVD | publisher = MGM Home Entertainment Inc. |accessdate =4 August 2007 | url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0322765/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media |year=2000 |title= Inside The Living Daylights |medium= DVD | publisher= MGM Home Entertainment Inc. |accessdate =4 August 2007 | url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0307015/}}</ref> In her initial scene with Klebb, Tatiana refers to training for the ballet, referencing the actress's real life background.\n\nGreek actress [[Katina Paxinou]] was originally considered for the role of Rosa Klebb, but was unavailable. Terence Young cast Austrian singer Lotte Lenya after hearing one of her musical recordings. Young wanted Kronsteen's portrayer to be \"an actor with a remarkable face\", so the minor character would be well remembered by audiences. This led to the casting of [[Vladek Sheybal]], whom Young also considered convincing as an intellectual.<ref name=\"young\">{{Cite AV media |author=[[Terence Young (director)|Terence Young]] |title=From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]] |location=''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1 |publisher= MGM Home Entertainment |id= Accessed 17 October 2008}}</ref> Several women were tested for the roles of Vida and Zora, the two fighting Gypsy girls, and after [[Aliza Gur]] and [[Martine Beswick]] were cast, they spent six weeks practising their fight choreography with stunt work arranger Peter Perkins.<ref>{{Cite AV media |author=[[Aliza Gur]] |title= From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]] |location= ''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1 |publisher = MGM Home Entertainment |id= Accessed 20 October 2008}}</ref> Beswick was mis-credited as 'Martin Beswick' in the film's opening titles, but this error was fixed for the 2001 DVD release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.007museum.com/from_russia_with_love.htm|title=From Russia with Love|website=www.007museum.com}}</ref>\n\nMexican actor [[Pedro Armend\u00e1riz]] was recommended to Young by director [[John Ford]] to play Kerim Bey. After experiencing increasing discomfort on location in Istanbul, Armend\u00e1riz was diagnosed with inoperable cancer. Filming in Istanbul was terminated, the production moved to Britain, and Armend\u00e1riz's scenes were brought forward so that he could complete his scenes without delay. Though visibly in pain, he continued working as long as possible. When he could no longer work, he returned home and took his own life.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\" /> Remaining shots after Armend\u00e1riz left London had a [[stunt double]] and Terence Young himself as stand-ins.<ref name=\"booklet\" />\n\nEnglishman [[Joe Robinson (actor)|Joe Robinson]] was a strong contender for the role of [[Red Grant]] but it was given to Robert Shaw.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thevisitor.co.uk/news/morecambe-and-district-news/joe_has_eye_of_the_tiger_1_1217122|title=Joe has eye of the Tiger |date=10 August 2004 |work= [[The Visitor (Morecambe newspaper)|The Visitor]]}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n{{See also|List of James Bond vehicles|List of James Bond gadgets|James Bond locations}}\nMost of the film was set in Istanbul, Turkey. Locations included the [[Basilica Cistern]], Hagia Sophia and the [[\u0130stanbul Sirkeci Terminal|Sirkeci railway station]], which also was used for the [[Belgrade]] and [[Zagreb]] railway stations. The MI6 office in London, SPECTRE Island, the Venice hotel and the interior scenes of the Orient Express were filmed at [[Pinewood Studios]] with some footage of the train. In the film, the train journey was set in [[Eastern Europe]]. The journey and the truck ride were shot in [[Argyll]], Scotland and [[Switzerland]]. The end scenes for the film were shot in [[Venice]].<ref name=\"insideFRWL\">{{Cite AV media |year=2000 |title= Inside From Russia with Love |medium = DVD |publisher = MGM Home Entertainment Inc. |people = Martine Beswick, Daniela Bianchi, Dana Broccoli, Syd Cain, Sean Connery, Peter Hunt, John Stears, Norman Wanstall |accessdate =4 August 2007 |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0322760/}}</ref> However, to qualify for the British film funding of the time, at least 70 percent of the film had to have been filmed in Great Britain or the Commonwealth.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Barnes |first1=Alan |last2=Hearn |first2=Marcu |year=1997 |title=Kiss Kiss Bang! Bang!: the Unofficial James Bond Film Companion |publisher= [[Batsford Books]] |isbn= 978-0-7134-8182-2 |page=23}}</ref> The Gypsy camp was also to be filmed in an actual camp in [[Topkap\u0131 Palace|Topkapi]], but was actually shot in a replica of it in Pinewood.<ref name=\"commentary\"/> The scene with rats (after the theft of the Lektor) was shot in Spain, as Britain did not allow filming with wild rats, and an attempt to film white rats painted in cocoa in Turkey did not work.<ref>{{Cite AV media |author=[[Syd Cain]] |title= From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]] |location=''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1|publisher = MGM Home Entertainment |id= Accessed 20 October 2008}}</ref> Principal photography began on 1 April 1963,<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> and wrapped on 23 August.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Barnes |first1=Alan |last2=Hearn |first2=Marcu |year=1997 |title=Kiss Kiss Bang! Bang!: the Unofficial James Bond Film Companion |publisher= [[Batsford Books]] |isbn= 978-0-7134-8182-2 |page=24}}</ref> Ian Fleming spent a week in the Istanbul shoot, supervising production and touring the city with the producers.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lycett|first=Andrew|authorlink=Andrew Lycett|title=Ian Fleming|year=1996|publisher=Phoenix|location=London|isbn=978-1-85799-783-5|page=418}}</ref><ref name=hero>{{cite book|title=Some Kind of Hero: The Remarkable Story of the James Bond Films|author1=Field, Matthew |author2=Chowdhury, Ajay |publisher=The History Press|year=2015|isbn=978-0750966504|page=102}}</ref>\n\nDirector Terence Young's eye for realism was evident throughout production. For the opening chess match, Kronsteen wins the game with a reenactment of [[Boris Spassky]]'s victory over [[David Bronstein]] in 1960.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.chessbase.com/newsprint.asp?newsid=1882|title=The name is Spassky \u2013 Boris Spassky |publisher= ChessBase.com |date=2 September 2004 |accessdate=16 February 2008 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121007073815/http://www.chessbase.com/newsprint.asp?newsid=1882 |archivedate=7 October 2012 }}</ref> Production Designer Syd Cain built up the \"chess pawn\" motif in his $150,000 set for the brief sequence.<ref name=\"commentary\"/> Cain also later added a promotion to another movie Eon was producing, making Krilencu's death happen inside a billboard for ''[[Call Me Bwana]]''.<ref name=hero/> A noteworthy gadget featured was the [[attach\u00e9 case]] (briefcase) issued by Q Branch. It had a tear gas bomb that detonated if the case was improperly opened, a folding [[AR-7]] [[sniper rifle]] with twenty rounds of ammunition, a throwing knife, and 50 [[Sovereign (British coin)|gold sovereigns]]. A boxer at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], Young choreographed the fight between Grant and Bond along with stunt coordinator Peter Perkins. The scene took three weeks to film and was violent enough to worry some on the production. Robert Shaw and Connery did most of the stunts themselves.<ref name=\"booklet\"/><ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/>\n\nAfter the unexpected loss of Armend\u00e1riz, production proceeded, experiencing complications from uncredited rewrites by [[Berkely Mather]] during filming. Editor [[Peter R. Hunt|Peter Hunt]] set about editing the film while key elements were still to be filmed, helping to restructure the opening scenes. Hunt and Young came up with the idea of moving the Red Grant training sequence to the beginning of the film (prior to the main title), a signature feature that has been an enduring hallmark of every Bond film since. The briefing with Blofeld was rewritten, and back projection was used to refilm Lotte Lenya's lines.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/>\n\nBehind schedule and over-budget, the production crew struggled to complete production in time for the already-announced premiere date that October. On 6 July 1963, while scouting locations in Argyll, Scotland, for that day's filming of the climactic boat chase, Terence Young's helicopter crashed into the water with art director Michael White and a cameraman aboard. The craft sank into 40\u201350 feet (12\u201315&nbsp;m) of water<!-- John Stears -->, but all escaped with minor injuries. Despite the calamity, Young was behind the camera for the full day's work. A few days later, Bianchi's driver fell asleep during the commute to a 6&nbsp;am shoot and crashed the car. The actress's face was bruised and Bianchi's scenes had to be delayed for two weeks while the facial contusions healed.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/>\n\nThe helicopter and boat chase scenes were not in the original novel but were added to create an action climax. The former was inspired by the crop-dusting scene in [[Alfred Hitchcock|Hitchcock's]] ''[[North by Northwest]]'' and the latter by a previous Young/Broccoli/Maibaum collaboration, ''[[The Red Beret]]''.<ref name=\"cork\" /> These two scenes would initially be shot in Istanbul but were moved to Scotland. The speedboats could not go fast enough due to the many waves in the sea,<ref name=\"gotell\"/> and a rented boat filled with cameras ended up sinking in the Bosphorus.<ref name=\"commentary\"/> A helicopter was also hard to obtain, and the special effects crew were nearly arrested trying to get one at a local airbase.<ref name=\"gotell\">{{Cite AV media |author=[[Walter Gotell]] |title=From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]]|location=''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1|publisher = MGM Home Entertainment |id= Accessed 17 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media |author=[[John Stears]] |title=From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]] |location= ''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1 |publisher = MGM Home Entertainment |id= Accessed 17 October 2008}}</ref> The helicopter chase was filmed with a [[radio control]]led miniature helicopter.<ref name=\"commentary\"/> The sounds of the boat chase were replaced in post-production since the boats were not loud enough,<ref>{{Cite AV media |author=Norman Wanstall |title= From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]] |location= ''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1 |publisher = MGM Home Entertainment |id= Accessed 20 October 2008}}</ref> and the explosion, shot in Pinewood, got out of control, burning [[Walter Gotell]]'s eyelids<ref name=\"gotell\" /> and seriously injuring three stuntmen.<ref name=\"cork\">{{Cite AV media |author=John Cork |title= From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]] |location= ''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1 |publisher = MGM Home Entertainment |id= Accessed 20 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nPhotographer [[David Hurn]] was commissioned by the producers of the [[James Bond]] films to shoot a series of stills with [[Sean Connery]] and the actresses of the film. When the [[theatrical property]] [[Walther PPK]] pistol did not arrive, Hurn volunteered the use of his own Walther LP-53 [[air pistol]].<ref>\"http://christies.com/LotFinder/lot_details.aspx?from=searchresults&intObjectID=1992033</ref> Though the photographs of the \"James Bond is Back\" posters of the US release airbrushed out the long barrel of the pistol, [[film poster]] artist Renato Fratini used the long-barrelled pistol for his drawings of Connery on the British posters.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bfi.org.uk/filmtvinfo/library/eventsexh/past/2007_01_10_bond.html|title=Poster Galore |publisher= [[British Film Institute]]|date=10 January 2007 |accessdate=8 February 2011 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120309163839/http://www.bfi.org.uk/filmtvinfo/library/eventsexh/past/2007_01_10_bond.html |archivedate=9 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nFor the opening credits, Maurice Binder had disagreements with the producers and did not want to return.<ref>''[[Starlog (magazine)|Starlog]]'' magazine Maurice Binder interview Part 1</ref> Designer Robert Brownjohn stepped into his place, and projected the credits on female dancers, inspired by [[Constructivism (art)|constructivist]] artist [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Moholy-Nagy]] projecting light onto clouds in the 1920s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.designmuseum.org/design/robert-brownjohn |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-07-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110623223840/http://designmuseum.org/design/robert-brownjohn |archivedate=23 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Brownjohn's work started the tradition of scantily clad women in the Bond films' title sequences.<ref name=growup>{{cite book |title= \"Grow Up, 007!\" \u2013 James Bond Over the Decades: Formula Vs. Innovation |first=Kerstin |last=J\u00fctting |publisher= GRIN Verlag |year=2007 |isbn= 978-3-638-85372-9|page=13 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=MzuVat9N7bQC&pg=PA12}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{See also|From Russia with Love (soundtrack)}}\n\n''From Russia with Love'' is the first Bond film in the series with John Barry as the primary soundtrack composer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://restless.rimspace.net/soundtrack/fff/from_russia_with_love.htm|title=\"From Russia with Love\" (1963) at Soundtrack Incomplete|accessdate=28 July 2007|publisher=Loki Carbis|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070816071109/http://restless.rimspace.net/soundtrack/fff/from_russia_with_love.htm |archivedate = 16 August 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The theme song was composed by [[Lionel Bart]] of ''[[Oliver!]]'' fame and sung by [[Matt Monro]],<ref name=\"James Bond Theme\">{{cite web|url=http://www.listology.com/content_show.cfm/content_id.10101|title=Listology: Rating the James Bond Theme Songs|accessdate=28 July 2007|publisher=Listology.com}}</ref> although the title credit music is a lively instrumental version of the tune beginning with Barry's brief \"James Bond Is Back\" then segueing into [[Monty Norman]]'s \"[[James Bond Theme]]\". Monro's vocal version is later played during the film (as source music on a radio) and properly over the film's end titles.<ref name=\"James Bond Theme\" /> Barry travelled with the crew to Turkey to try getting influences of the local music, but ended up using almost nothing, just local instruments such as [[Zill|finger cymbals]] to give an exotic feeling, since he thought the Turkish music had a comedic tone that did not fit in the \"dramatic feeling\" of the James Bond movies.<ref name=\"barry\">{{Cite AV media|author=[[John Barry (composer)|John Barry]]|title=From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]]|location=''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1|publisher = MGM Home Entertainment }}</ref>\n\nRecalling his visit to Istanbul, John Barry said, \"It was like no place I'd ever been in my life. [The Trip] was supposedly to seep up the music, so Noel Rogers and I used to go 'round to these nightclubs and listen to all this stuff. We had the strangest week, and really came away with nothing, except a lot of ridiculous stories. We went back, talked to Lionel, and then he wrote 'From Russia with Love.<nowiki>'''</nowiki><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Music_of_James_Bond.html?id=wQE2RmHrErcC|title=The Music of James Bond|last=Burlingame|first=Jon|date=2012-11-01|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199986767|location=|pages=25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn this film, Barry introduced the percussive theme \"[[007 Theme|007]]\"\u2014action music that came to be considered the \"secondary James Bond theme\". He composed it to have a lighter, enthusiastic and more adventurous theme to relax the audience.<ref name=\"barry\"/> The arrangement appears twice on the soundtrack album; the second version, entitled \"007 Takes the Lektor\", is the one used during the gunfight at the Gypsy camp and also during Bond's theft of the Lektor decoding machine.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/><ref name=\"music\">{{Cite AV media |year=2000 | title = The Music of James Bond | medium = DVD | publisher = MGM Home Entertainment Inc. |accessdate =4 August 2007 | url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0307198/}}</ref> The completed film features a holdover from the Monty Norman-supervised ''Dr. No'' music; the post-rocket-launch music from ''Dr. No'' is played in ''From Russia with Love'' during the helicopter and speedboat attacks.<ref name=\"music\"/>\n\n==Release and reception==\n''From Russia with Love'' premiered on 10 October 1963 at the [[Odeon Leicester Square]] in London.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Premium for Bond-Lovers:\"From Russia with Love\"|newspaper=[[The Illustrated London News]]|date=5 October 1963|location=London|page=527}}</ref> Ian Fleming, Sean Connery and Walter Gotell attended the premiere. The following year, it was released in 16 countries worldwide, with the United States premiere on 8 April 1964, at New York's [[Astor Theatre, New York City|Astor Theatre]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Sean Connery: a celebration|first=Robert|last=Sellers|publisher=Robert Hale|year=1999|isbn=978-0-7090-6125-0|page=66}}</ref> Upon its first release, ''From Russia with Love'' doubled ''Dr. No''{{'}}s gross by earning $12.5 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|12.5|1964}}}} million in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US|df=yes}}) at the worldwide box office.<ref>{{cite book|title=United Artists, Volume 2, 1951\u20131978: The Company That Changed the Film Industry|first=Tino|last=Balio|publisher=[[University of Wisconsin Press]]|year=2009|isbn=978-0-299-23014-2|page=261|quote=The picture grossed twice as much as ''Dr. No'', both foreign and domestic \u2013 $12.5 million worldwide}}</ref> After reissue it grossed $78 million,<ref name=\"NumbersBO\">{{cite web|url=http://the-numbers.com/movies/1964/0FRLW.php|title=From Russia with Love|work=The Numbers|publisher=Nash Information Service|accessdate=16 March 2008}}</ref> of which $24 million was from North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=fromrussiawithlove.htm|title=From Russia, with Love (1964)|accessdate=28 July 2007|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref> It was the most popular movie at the British box office in 1963.<ref>{{cite news|title=Most Popular Films of 1963|newspaper=[[The Times]]|date=3 January 1964|location=London|page=4}}</ref>\n\nThe film's cinematographer [[Ted Moore]] won the [[BAFTA]] award and the [[British Society of Cinematographers]] award for Best Cinematography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1800068321/awards|title=Awards at Yahoo Movies|accessdate=30 July 2007}}</ref> At the 1965 Laurel Awards, Lotte Lenya stood third for Best Female Supporting Performance, and the film secured second place in the Action-Drama category. The film was also nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]] for \"[[From Russia with Love (soundtrack)|From Russia with Love]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0057076/awards|title=Awards won by From Russia with Love|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]] | accessdate=1 August 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Contemporary reviews===\nIn comparing the film to its predecessor, ''Dr. No'', [[Richard Roud]], writing in ''[[The Guardian]]'', said that ''From Russia with Love'' \"didn't seem quite so lively, quite so fresh, or quite so rhythmically fast-moving.\"<ref name=\"Roud (1963)\">{{cite news|last=Roud|first=Richard|title=New Films|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 October 1963|authorlink=Richard Roud|location=London|page=11}}</ref> He went on to say that \"...&nbsp;the film is highly immoral in every imaginable way; it is neither uplifting, instructive nor life-enhancing. Neither is it great film-making. But it sure is fun.\"<ref name=\"Roud (1963)\"/> Writing in ''[[The Observer]]'', [[Penelope Gilliatt]] noted that \"The way the credits are done has the same self-mocking flamboyance as everything else in the picture.\"<ref name=\"Gilliatt (1963)\">{{cite news|last=Gilliatt|first=Penelope|title=Laughing it off with Bond: Films|newspaper=[[The Observer]]|date=13 October 1963|authorlink=Penelope Gilliatt|location=London|page=27}}</ref> Gilliatt went on to say that the film manages \"to keep up its own cracking pace, nearly all the way. The set-pieces are a stunning box of tricks\".<ref name=\"Gilliatt (1963)\"/> The critic for ''[[The Times]]'' wrote of Bond that he is \"the secret ideal of the congenital square, conventional in every particular&nbsp;... except in morality, where he has the courage\u2014and the physical equipment\u2014to do without thinking what most of us feel we might be doing&nbsp;...\"<ref name=\"Times (1963)\">{{cite news|title=Four Just Men Rolled into One|newspaper=[[The Times]]|date=10 October 1963|location=London|page=17}}</ref> The critic thought that overall, \"the nonsense is all very amiable and tongue-in-cheek and will no doubt make a fortune for its devisers\".<ref name=\"Times (1963)\"/>\n\n[[Bosley Crowther]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said: \"Don't miss it! This is to say, don't miss it if you can still get the least bit of fun out of lurid adventure fiction and pseudo-realistic fantasy. For this mad melodramatization of a desperate adventure of Bond with sinister characters in Istanbul and on the Orient Express is fictional exaggeration on a grand scale and in a dashing style, thoroughly illogical and improbable, but with tongue blithely wedged in cheek.\"<ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1964/04/09/archives/james-bond-travels-the-orient-express.html| title = James Bond Travels the Orient Express | date = 9 April 1964 | accessdate=11 May 2009| last=Crowther |first=Bosley | authorlink=Bosley Crowther|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine called the film \"fast, smart, shrewdly directed and capably performed\"<ref name=\"Time (1964)\">{{cite magazine| url= http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,875772,00.html | title= Once More Unto the Breach | magazine= [[Time (magazine)|Time]] | volume=83 | issue=15 | date=10 April 1964 | accessdate=11 May 2009}}</ref> and commented extensively on the film's humour, saying \"Director Young is a master of the form he ridicules, and in almost every episode he hands the audience shocks as well as yocks. But the yocks are more memorable. They result from slight but sly infractions of the thriller formula. A Russian agent, for instance, does not simply escape through a window; no, he escapes through a window in a brick wall painted with a colossal poster portrait of [[Anita Ekberg]], and as he crawls out of the window, he seems to be crawling out of Anita's mouth. Or again, Bond does not simply train a telescope on the Russian consulate and hope he can read somebody's lips; no, he makes his way laboriously into a gallery beneath the joint, runs a submarine periscope up through the walls, and there, at close range, inspects two important Soviet secrets: the heroine's legs.\"<ref name=\"Time (1964)\"/>\n\n===Reflective reviews=== <!-- do not rename this section without fixing the intro's forward reference -->\n''From Russia with Love'' received generally positive reviews from critics; [[Rotten Tomatoes]] sampled 57 reviewers and judged 95% of the reviews to be positive with a rating of 8/10. Its summary states: \"The second James Bond film, ''From Russia with Love'', is a razor-sharp, briskly-paced Cold War thriller that features several electrifying action scenes.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=From Russia With Love (1963)|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/from_russia_with_love/|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> Many online sites also commonly cite ''From Russia with Love'' as the best Bond film of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://commanderbond.net/2750/cbn-reviews-from-russia-with-love.html|title=CBn Reviews 'From Russia With Love'|last=Zydel|first=Devin|publisher=CBn|accessdate=29 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn his 1986 book, [[Danny Peary]] described ''From Russia with Love'' as \"an excellent, surprisingly tough and gritty James Bond film\" which is \"refreshingly free of the gimmickry that would characterise the later Bond films, and Connery and Bianchi play ''real'' people. We worry about them and hope their relationship will work out&nbsp;... Shaw and Lotte Lenya are splendid villains. Both have exciting, well-choreographed fights with Connery. Actors play it straight, with excellent results.\"<ref>Danny Peary, ''Guide for the Film Fanatic'' (Simon & Schuster, 1986) p.163</ref>\n\nFilm critic [[James Berardinelli]] cited this as his favourite Bond film, writing \"Only ''From Russia with Love'' avoids slipping into the comic book realm of ''Goldfinger'' and its successors while giving us a sampling of the familiar Bond formula (action, gadgets, women, cars, etc.). ''From Russia with Love'' is effectively paced and plotted, features a gallery of detestable rogues (including the ultimate Bond villain, Blofeld), and offers countless thrills\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://preview.reelviews.net/top100/103.html|title=Top 100 Runner Up: From Russia with Love|publisher=Reelviews|author=Berardinelli, James|accessdate=16 March 2008|authorlink=James Berardinelli}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2001 Neil Smith of ''[[BBC]] Films'' called it \"a film that only gets better with age\".<ref>{{cite web| title=From Russia with Love (1963)| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2001/06/19/from_russia_with_love_1963_review.shtml|publisher=BBC| date=19 June 2001 | accessdate=16 March 2008}}</ref> In 2004, ''[[Total Film]]'' magazine named it the ninth-greatest British film of all time, making it the only James Bond film to appear on the list.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3711460.stm |title=Get Carter tops British film poll |accessdate=28 July 2007 |date=3 October 2004 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> In 2006, Jay Antani of Filmcritic praised the film's \"impressive staging of action scenes\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmcritic.com/misc/emporium.nsf/reviews/From-Russia-with-Love|title=From Russia with Love|last=Antani|first=Jay|publisher=Filmcritic.com|accessdate=16 March 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214102052/http://www.filmcritic.com/reviews/1963/from-russia-with-love/|archivedate=14 February 2012}}</ref> while [[IGN]] listed it as second-best Bond film ever, behind only ''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/746/746573p4.html|title=James Bond's Top 20|publisher=IGN|date=17 November 2006|accessdate=4 March 2008}}</ref> That same year, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' put the film at ninth among Bond films, criticising the slow pace.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1560072_14,00.html|title=Ranking the Bond Films|author=Benjamin Svetkey, Joshua Rich|date=15 November 2006|accessdate=16 March 2008|work=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref> When the \"James Bond Ultimate Collector's Set\" was released in November 2007 by MGM, Norman Wilner of [[MSN]] chose ''From Russia with Love'' as the best Bond film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.sympatico.msn.ca/features/ArticleNormanWilner.aspx?cp-documentid=436189|title=Rating the Spy Game|publisher=[[MSN]]|author=Norman Wilner|accessdate=4 March 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080119210839/http://movies.sympatico.msn.ca/features/ArticleNormanWilner.aspx?cp-documentid=436189|archivedate=19 January 2008}}</ref> Conversely, in his book about the Bond phenomenon, ''The Man With the Golden Touch,'' British author Sinclair McKay states \"I know it is heresy to say so, and that some enthusiasts regard ''From Russia With Love'' as the Holy Grail of Bond, but let's be searingly honest \u2013 some of it is crashingly dull.\"<ref>McKay, Sinclair. ''The Man With the Golden Touch.'' Overlook Press: New York. 2008. Pg. 4</ref>\nIn 2014 ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' polled several film critics, directors, actors and stunt actors to list their top action films;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/film/best-action-movies|work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|title=The 100 best action movies|accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref> ''From Russia With Love'' was listed at 69.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/film/the-100-best-action-movies-70-61?package_page%3D23379 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-03-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150312133940/http://www.timeout.com/newyork/film/the-100-best-action-movies-70-61?package_page=23379 |archivedate=12 March 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThe [[British Film Institute]]'s [[screenonline]] guide called the film \"one of the series' high points\" and said it \"had advantages not enjoyed by many later Bond films, notably an intelligent script that retained the substance of [[From Russia, with Love (novel)|Ian Fleming's novel]] while toning down the overt Cold War politics (the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] had only occurred the previous year).\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/520462/ |title=From Russia With Love (1963) |author=Michael Brooke |work=[[screenonline]] |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |accessdate=11 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6gse0OdyO |archivedate=19 April 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 2008, [[Michael G. Wilson]], the current co-producer of the series, stated \"We always start out trying to make another ''From Russia with Love'' and end up with another ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.askmen.com/entertainment/movie/from-russia-with-love.html|title=From Russia With Love|last=Nusair|first=David|publisher=AskMen|date=1 November 2008| accessdate=28 February 2009}}</ref> Sean Connery,<ref name=\"booklet\"/> Michael G. Wilson, Barbara Broccoli, Timothy Dalton and Daniel Craig also consider this their favourite Bond film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmmonthly.com/paul_fischer_profiles/broccoli_and_wilson_rejuvenate_bond_franchise.html|title=Broccoli and Wilson Rejuvenate Bond Franchise|last=Fischer|first=Paul|publisher=FilmMonthly|accessdate=27 March 2010|year=2008}}</ref> [[Albert Broccoli]] listed it with ''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]'' and ''[[The Spy Who Loved Me (film)|The Spy Who Loved Me]]'' as one of his top three favourites,<ref>{{cite web|author=COLIN M JARMAN |url=http://www.licensetoquote.com/2010/06/in-memory-albert-cubby-broccoli.html |title=IN MEMORY: Albert 'Cubby' Broccoli \u2013 The Mastermind behind the James Bond movies |publisher=Licensetoquote.com |date=27 June 2010 |accessdate=21 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713204045/http://www.licensetoquote.com/2010/06/in-memory-albert-cubby-broccoli.html |archivedate=13 July 2011 }}</ref> explaining that he felt \"it was with this film that the Bond style and formula were perfected\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Licence to thrill: a cultural history of the James Bond films|first=James |last=Chapman|publisher=I. B. Tauris|year=2007|isbn=978-1-84511-515-9}}</ref>\n\n==Video game adaptation==\n{{Main|From Russia with Love (video game)}}\nIn 2005, the ''[[From Russia with Love (video game)|From Russia with Love]]'' video game was developed by [[Electronic Arts]] and released on 1 November 2005 in North America. It follows the storyline of the book and film, albeit adding in new scenes, making it more action-oriented. One of the most significant changes to the story is the replacement of the organisation [[SPECTRE]] to OCTOPUS because the name SPECTRE constituted a long-running [[Thunderball (novel)#Controversy|legal dispute]] over the film rights to ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]'' between United Artists/MGM and writer [[Kevin McClory]]. Most of the cast from the film returned in likeness. Connery not only allowed his 1960s likeness as Bond to be used, but the actor, in his 70s, also recorded the character's dialogue, marking a return to the role 22 years after he last played Bond in ''[[Never Say Never Again]]''. Featuring a [[virtual camera system|third-person]] [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] [[deathmatch]] mode, the game depicts several elements of later Bond films, such as the [[Aston Martin DB5]] from ''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]'' (1964) and the rocket belt from ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]'' (1965).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cube.gamespy.com/gamecube/james-bond-007-from-russia-with-love/654415p1.html|title=Interview with David Carson|publisher=[[GameSpy]]|date=29 September 2005|access-date=8 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/fromrussiawithlove/review.html|title=From Russia With Love Review|last=Navarro|first=Alex|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|date=1 November 2005|access-date=8 February 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130324041325/http://www.gamespot.com/from-russia-with-love/reviews/from-russia-with-love-review-6137026/|archivedate=24 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe game was penned by [[Bruce Feirstein]], who had previously worked on the film scripts for ''[[GoldenEye]]'', ''[[Tomorrow Never Dies]]'', ''[[The World Is Not Enough]]'', and the 2004 video game, ''[[James Bond 007: Everything or Nothing|Everything or Nothing]]''. Its soundtrack was composed by [[Christopher Lennertz]] and [[Vic Flick]].<ref>{{Cite video game|title = [[From Russia with Love (video game)|From Russia with Love]]|developer = [[Electronic Arts]]| date =1 November 2005}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portalbar|1960s|Film|United Kingdom}}\n* [[Outline of James Bond]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=N}}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Peary |first=Danny |authorlink=Danny Peary |title=Cult Movie Stars |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KHhZAAAAMAAJ |year=1991 |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |location=New York |isbn=978-0-671-74924-8 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Rubin |first=Steven Jay |title=The Complete James Bond Movie Encyclopedia |year=2003 |publisher=[[McGraw-Hill|Contemporary Books]] |location=New York |isbn=978-0-07-141246-9 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/dvdsavant/s2065russjump2.html |title=Jump Cut 3: The British Censorship of From Russia with Love from research by Gavin Salkeld |last1=Erickson |first1=Glenn |date=22 July 2006 |publisher=DVDTalk.com |accessdate=30 June 2013}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|From Russia with Love (film)}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.webcitation.org/6gse0OdyO?url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/520462/ ''From Russia With Love''] at [[BFI Screenonline]]\n* {{IMDb title|0057076|From Russia with Love}}\n* {{tcmdb title|75744|From Russia with Love}}\n* {{Amg movie|18751|From Russia with Love}}\n* {{AFI film|id=22487|title=From Russia with Love}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|from_russia_with_love|From Russia with Love}}\n* {{mojo title|fromrussiawithlove|From Russia with Love}}\n* [http://www.mgm.com/title_title.do?title_star=FROMRUSS From Russia With Love] from [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]]\n\n{{James Bond films}}\n{{JB SMERSH stories}}\n{{SPECTRE stories}}\n{{Terence Young}}\n{{Harry Saltzman|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:From Russia With Love (Film)}}\n[[Category:1960s action films]]\n[[Category:1960s spy films]]\n[[Category:1960s thriller films]]\n[[Category:1960s sequel films]]\n[[Category:1963 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:American spy films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British sequel films]]\n[[Category:British spy films]]\n[[Category:Cold War espionage]]\n[[Category:Cold War spy films]]\n[[Category:Defection in fiction]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Barry (composer)]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Terence Young]]\n[[Category:Films set in Istanbul]]\n[[Category:Films set in London]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Films set on trains]]\n[[Category:Films set in Venice]]\n[[Category:Films set in Yugoslavia]]\n[[Category:Films set on the Orient Express]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Argyll and Bute]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Berkshire]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Buckinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Gwynedd]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Istanbul]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Madrid]]\n[[Category:Foreign films shot in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Venice]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Wales]]\n[[Category:From Russia with Love (film)| ]]\n[[Category:James Bond films]]\n[[Category:Films shot at Pinewood Studios]]\n[[Category:Rail transport films]]\n[[Category:Films about Romani people]]\n[[Category:United Artists films]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Johanna Harwood]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Richard Maibaum]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Berkely Mather]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Harry Saltzman]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Albert R. Broccoli]]\n[[Category:Films set in Zagreb]]\n[[Category:Films set in Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Eon Productions films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1963 film in the James Bond series directed by Terence Young}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = From Russia with Love\n| image          = From Russia with Love \u2013 UK cinema poster.jpg\n| border         = yes\n| caption        = British [[cinema poster]] for ''From Russia with Love'', designed and illustrated by [[Renato Fratini]] and [[Eric Pulford]]\n| alt            = The upper centre of the poster reads \"Meet James Bond, secret agent 007. His new incredible women&nbsp;... His new incredible enemies&nbsp;... His new incredible adventures&nbsp;...\" To the right is Bond holding a gun, to the left a montage of women, fights, and an explosion. On the bottom of the poster are the credits.\n| starring       = [[Sean Connery]]<br />[[Pedro Armend\u00e1riz]]<br />[[Lotte Lenya]]<br />[[Robert Shaw (British actor)|Robert Shaw]]<br />[[Bernard Lee]]<br />[[Daniela Bianchi]]\n| screenplay     = [[Richard Maibaum]]<br />[[Berkely Mather]] {{small|(uncredited)}}\n| story          = [[Johanna Harwood]]\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[From Russia, with Love (novel)|From Russia, with Love]]''|[[Ian Fleming]]}}\n| cinematography = [[Ted Moore]]\n| director       = [[Terence Young (director)|Terence Young]]\n| producer       = [[Harry Saltzman]]<br />[[Albert R. Broccoli]]\n| music          = [[John Barry (composer)|John Barry]]\n| editing        = [[Peter R. Hunt]]\n| studio         = [[Eon Productions]]\n| distributor    = [[United Artists]]\n| released       = {{Film date|df=yes|1963|10|10|London, premiere|1963|10|11|United Kingdom|1964|4|8|United States}}\n| runtime        = 115 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom<br />United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $2 million\n| gross          = $79 million\n}}\n'''''From Russia with Love''''' is a 1963 [[spy film]] and the second in the [[List of James Bond films|''James Bond'' series]] produced by [[Eon Productions]], as well as [[Sean Connery]]'s second role as [[MI6]] agent [[James Bond]]. It was directed by [[Terence Young (director)|Terence Young]], produced by [[Albert R. Broccoli]] and [[Harry Saltzman]], and written by [[Richard Maibaum]] and [[Johanna Harwood]], based on [[Ian Fleming]]'s [[From Russia, with Love (novel)|similarly named 1957 novel]]. In the film, Bond is sent to assist in the defection of Soviet [[consulate]] clerk [[Tatiana Romanova]] in [[Turkey]], where [[SPECTRE]] plans to avenge Bond's killing of [[Julius No|Dr. No]].\n\nFollowing the success of ''[[Dr. No (film)|Dr. No]]'', [[United Artists]] greenlit a sequel and doubled the budget available for the producers. In addition to filming on location in Turkey, the action scenes were shot at [[Pinewood Studios]], [[Buckinghamshire]], and in [[Scotland]]. Production ran over budget and schedule, and was rushed to finish by its scheduled October 1963 release date.\n\n''From Russia with Love'' was a critical and commercial success. It took in more than $78 million in worldwide box-office receipts, far more than its $2 million budget and more than its predecessor ''Dr. No'', thereby becoming a [[blockbuster (entertainment)|blockbuster]] in 1960s cinema.\n\nThis film also marked the debut of [[Desmond Llewelyn]] as [[Q (James Bond)|Q]], a role he would play for 36 years (and seventeen films) until ''[[The World Is Not Enough]]'' in 1999.\n\n== Plot ==\nSeeking revenge against [[Secret Intelligence Service|MI6]] Agent 007 [[James Bond]] for the death of their agent [[Julius No|Dr. No]] in [[Jamaica]],{{refn|name=Timeline|group=N|As depicted in the 1962 film ''[[Dr. No (film)|Dr. No]]''.}} international criminal organisation [[SPECTRE]] begins training agents to kill him. Irish assassin Donald \"Red\" Grant proves himself by quickly killing a fake Bond with a [[garrote]] concealed in his wristwatch during training.\n\nSPECTRE's chief planner, [[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic|Czech]] chess [[Grandmaster (chess)|grandmaster]] Kronsteen (Number 5), devises a plan to play British and Soviet intelligence against each other to procure a Lektor [[cryptography]] device from the [[Soviet Union|Soviets]] and lure Bond to his assassination. SPECTRE's chief executive [[Ernst Stavro Blofeld|(Number 1)]] puts [[Rosa Klebb]] (Number 3), a former [[SMERSH]] (Soviet counter-intelligence) colonel, in charge of the mission. Klebb chooses Grant to protect Bond until he acquires the Lektor, then eliminate 007 and steal the machine for SPECTRE (to be eventually sold back to its legitimate owner). Klebb also recruits [[Tatiana Romanova]], a cipher clerk at the Soviet consulate in [[Istanbul]], who believes Klebb is still working for SMERSH.\n\nIn [[London]], [[M (James Bond)|M]] informs Bond that Romanova has contacted \"Station T\" in Turkey, offering to defect with a top-secret Lektor on the condition that Bond handle her case personally. M decides the chance of obtaining a Lektor is worth the risk, and [[Q (James Bond)|Q]] gives Bond an [[Briefcase|attach\u00e9 case]] with concealed throwing knife, gold sovereigns, a [[tear gas]] booby trap, and an [[ArmaLite AR-7]] sniper rifle.\n\nIn Istanbul, Bond meets station head [[List of James Bond allies#Film allies|Ali Kerim Bey]], tailed by [[People's Republic of Bulgaria|Bulgarian]] agents working for Russia, who are, in turn, tailed by Grant; he kills one agent and dumps their car outside the Soviet Consulate. The Soviets bomb Kerim's office with a [[limpet mine]], but he is away from his desk with his mistress. He and Bond spy on a Soviet consulate meeting through a periscope in the aqueducts beneath Istanbul, and learn that Soviet agent Krilencu is responsible for the bombing. Kerim and Bond lay low at a rural [[Romani people|gypsy]] settlement, where Krilencu attacks them with a band of Bulgarians; Bond is saved by a sniper shot from Grant. Bond and Kerim track down Krilencu, and Kerim kills him with Bond's rifle.\n\nBond finds Romanova in his hotel suite and they have sex, neither aware SPECTRE is filming them. Romanova brings the consulate floor plans to the Ayasofya M\u00fczesi, formally the [[Hagia Sophia]], and Grant kills the other Bulgarian to ensure Bond receives them. Using the plans, Bond and Kerim steal the Lektor and escape with Romanova aboard the ''[[Orient Express]]''. Kerim and Bond subdue a Soviet security officer named Benz tailing them. Grant kills Kerim and Benz, preventing Bond from rendezvousing with one of Kerim's men.\n\nAt the [[Belgrade]] station, Bond passes word of Kerim Bey's death to his son, and asks for an agent from [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Station Y]] to meet him at [[Zagreb]]. Grant kills Nash, sent from Station Y, and poses as the agent. After drugging Romanova at dinner, Grant overpowers Bond, taunting him that Romanova believed she was working for Mother Russia, and reveals his plan to leave the compromising film of Bond and Romanova with a blackmail letter, staging their deaths as a murder-suicide to scandalise the British intelligence community. Bond tricks Grant into setting off the booby trap in his attach\u00e9 case and stabs him with the concealed knife before strangling him with his own garrote, and flees with Romanova in Grant's getaway truck.\n\nNumber 1 confronts Klebb and Kronsteen for their failure. Kronsteen is executed by the henchman Morzeny's poison-tipped switchblade in his shoe, while Klebb is given one last chance to acquire the Lektor, which they have arranged to sell back to the Russians.\n\nFollowing Grant's escape route, Bond destroys a SPECTRE helicopter, and he and Romanova steal Grant's boat on the [[Dalmatia]]n coast. Pursued by Morzeny's squadron of SPECTRE powerboats, Bond detonates his own powerboat's fuel drums with a [[flare gun]], engulfing the pursuers in a sea of flames.\n\nHe and Romanova reach a hotel in [[Venice]], where they are attacked by Klebb, disguised as a maid. She tries to kick Bond with a poisoned switchblade shoe, but Romanova shoots her. Their mission accomplished, Bond and Romanova depart on a romantic boat ride, and Bond throws Grant's blackmail film into the canal.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Sean Connery]] as [[Portrayal of James Bond in film|James Bond]], [[Secret Intelligence Service|MI6]] agent 007.\n* [[Pedro Armend\u00e1riz]] as [[List of James Bond allies#Film-specific allies|Ali Kerim Bey]], head of MI6 Station T in Istanbul.\n* [[Lotte Lenya]] as [[Rosa Klebb|Rosa Klebb (SPECTRE No. 3)]], a former [[SMERSH (James Bond)|SMERSH]] colonel-turned-SPECTRE operative.\n* [[Robert Shaw (actor)|Robert Shaw]] as Donald \"Red\" Grant, a cunning SPECTRE assassin and one of the principal Bond enemies.\n* [[Daniela Bianchi]] as [[Tatiana Romanova]], a Soviet Consulate clerk and Bond's love interest. Fleming based Romanova on [[Krystyna Skarbek|Christine Granville]].<ref>''FILMFAX Magazine''. October 2003 \u2013 January 2004.</ref>\n**Bianchi's dialogue was dubbed by an uncredited [[Barbara Jefford]].<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite AV media notes|title=From Russia with Love Ultimate Edition DVD|others=[[Terence Young (director)|Terence Young]]|origyear=1962|publisher=MGM Home Entertainment|year=2006|id=Accessed 30 December 2007}}</ref> \n* [[Bernard Lee]] as [[M (James Bond)|M]], chief of British Intelligence.\n* [[Walter Gotell]] as Morzeny, a SPECTRE thug who trains personnel on SPECTRE Island. Gotell would go on to play a different character, [[List of James Bond allies#General Gogol|General Gogol]], in later entries in the series.\n* [[Vladek Sheybal]] as Kronsteen (SPECTRE No. 5), a [[Czechoslovakia|Czechoslovak]] chess [[Grandmaster (chess)|grandmaster]] and SPECTRE agent.\n*[[Anthony Dawson]] as [[Ernst Stavro Blofeld|Ernst Stavro Blofeld (SPECTRE No. 1)]], the head and mastermind of SPECTRE and Bond's nemesis. Dawson previously played Professor Dent in [[Dr. No (film)|''Dr. No'']]. He was credited [[Pseudonym|pseudonymously]] as \"?\" for the role.\n**Dawson's dialogue was dubbed by an uncredited [[Eric Pohlmann]].\n* [[Lois Maxwell]] as [[Miss Moneypenny]], M's secretary.\n* [[Desmond Llewelyn]] as [[Q (James Bond)|Major Boothroyd]], head of MI6 [[Q (James Bond)|Q Branch]], also called the \"Equipment Officer\"\n* [[Eunice Gayson]] as [[Eunice Gayson#Bond films|Sylvia Trench]], Bond's semi-regular girlfriend.\n**Gayson's dialogue was dubbed by an uncredited [[Nikki van der Zyl]].\n* [[Francis de Wolff]] as Vavra, chief of a Gypsy tribe used for dirty work by Kerim Bey.\n*Fred Haggerty as Krilencu, a Bulgarian assassin who works as a killer for the Soviets in the [[Balkans]].\n*[[Aliza Gur]] and [[Martine Beswick]] as Vida (in green) and Zora (in red), respectively, two jealous Gypsy girls who are disputing the same man.\n\nAdditional cast members include [[Peter Bayliss]] as Russian agent Commissar Benz, [[Peter Madden (actor)|Peter Madden]] as British chessmaster MacAdams, [[George Pastell]] as the [[Orient Express]] train conductor, [[Nadja Regin]] as Kerim Bey's lonely girlfriend, Nusret Ataer as Mehmet, Kerim Bey's son and agent, Neville Jason as Kerim Bey's chauffeur, [[Michael Culver]] and [[Elizabeth Counsell]] as a couple in a punt, William Hill as Captain Nash, a British agent killed and impersonated by Red Grant, and Lisa Guiraut as a Gypsy belly dancer.\n\n==Production==\nFollowing the financial success of ''Dr. No'', [[United Artists]] greenlit a second James Bond film. The studio doubled the budget offered to [[Eon Productions]] with $2 million, and also approved a bonus for Sean Connery, who would receive $100,000 along with his $54,000 salary.<ref>{{cite book|title=United Artists: the company that changed the film industry|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9EeK5s3aw44C&pg=PA260|first=Tino|last=Balio|page=260|publisher=[[University of Wisconsin]] Press|year=1987|isbn=9780299230135}}</ref> As [[John F. Kennedy|President John F. Kennedy]] had named Fleming's novel ''[[From Russia, with Love (novel)|From Russia with Love]]'' among his ten favourite books of all time in [[Life (magazine)|''Life'']] magazine,<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> producers Broccoli and Saltzman chose this as the follow-up to Bond's cinematic debut in ''[[Dr. No (film)|Dr. No]]''. ''From Russia with Love'' was the last film President Kennedy saw at the White House on 20 November 1963 before going to Dallas.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.prospect.org/cs/articles?article=arthur_m_schlesinger_jr_19172007 |title=Arthur M. Schlesinger, Jr., 1917\u20132007  |journal=The American Prospect |date=17 September 2010 |accessdate=21 September 2010}}</ref> Most of the crew from the first film returned, with major exceptions being production designer [[Ken Adam]], who went to work on ''[[Dr. Strangelove]]'' and was replaced by ''Dr. No''{{'}}s art director [[Syd Cain]]; title designer [[Maurice Binder]] was replaced by [[Robert Brownjohn]], and stunt coordinator [[Bob Simmons (stunt man)|Bob Simmons]] was unavailable and was replaced by Peter Perkins<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> though Simmons performed stunts in the film.<ref>Brosnan, John ''James Bond in the Cinema'' Tantivy Press; 2nd edition (1981)</ref> [[John Barry (composer)|John Barry]] replaced [[Monty Norman]] as composer of the soundtrack.\n\nThe film introduced several conventions which would become essential elements of the series: a [[pre-title sequence]], the Blofeld character (referred to in the film only as \"Number 1\") (though Blofeld is mentioned in the end credits, with the actor referred to only as \"?\"), a secret-weapon gadget for Bond, a helicopter sequence (repeated in every subsequent Bond film except ''[[The Man with the Golden Gun (film)|The Man with the Golden Gun]]''), a postscript action scene after the main climax, a theme song with lyrics, and the line \"James Bond will return/be back\" in the credits.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://whatculture.com/film/james-bond-retrospective-from-russia-with-love-1963|title=James Bond Retrospective: From Russia With Love (1963)|publisher=Whatculture|accessdate=22 September 2016|date=30 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Writing===\n[[Ian Fleming]]'s novel was a [[Cold War]] thriller but the producers replaced the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] undercover agency [[SMERSH]] with the crime syndicate SPECTRE so as to avoid controversial political overtones.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> The SPECTRE training grounds were inspired by the film ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]''.<ref name=\"young\"/> The original screenwriter was [[Len Deighton]], who accompanied Harry Saltzman, Syd Cain, and Terence Young to Istanbul<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hmssweblog.wordpress.com/2012/11/04/len-deighton-on-from-russia-with-love/ |title=Len Deighton on From Russia With Love &#124; The Spy Command |publisher=Hmssweblog.wordpress.com |date= 5 November 2012|accessdate=2016-09-30}}</ref> but he was replaced because of a lack of progress.<ref name=maibaum>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sWewbX79ISsC&pg=PA284|title=Backstory: interviews with screenwriters of Hollywood's golden age|author=McGilligan, Patrick|page=284|publisher=[[University of California Press]]|year=1986|isbn=978-0-520-05689-3|author-link=Patrick McGilligan (biographer)}}</ref> Thus, two of ''Dr. No''{{'}}s writers, [[Johanna Harwood]] and [[Richard Maibaum]], returned for the second film in the series.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> Some sources state Harwood was credited for the \"adaptation\" mostly for her suggestions which were carried over into Maibaum's script.<ref name=maibaum/> Harwood stated in an interview for ''Cinema Retro'' that she had been a screenwriter of several of Harry Saltzman's projects, and her screenplay for ''From Russia with Love'' had followed Fleming's novel closely, but she left the series due to what she called Terence Young's constant rewriting of her screenplay with ideas that were not in the original Fleming work.<ref>''Johanna Harwood Interview'' ''Movie Classics # 4'' Solo Publishing 2012</ref>\nMaibaum kept on making rewrites as filming progressed. Red Grant was added to the Istanbul scenes just prior to the film crew's trip to Turkey; this brought more focus to the SPECTRE plot, as Grant started saving Bond's life there (a late change during shooting involved Grant killing the bespectacled spy at Hagia Sophia instead of Bond, who ends up just finding the man dead).<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> For the last quarter of the movie, Maibaum added two chase scenes, with a helicopter and speedboats, and changed the location of Bond and Klebb's battle from Paris to Venice.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Chapman |first=James |year=2007 |title= Licence to Thrill |publisher= Cinema and Society |location= London/New York City |isbn=978-1-84511-515-9}}</ref> Uncredited rewrites were contributed by [[Berkely Mather]].\n\n===Casting===\nAlthough uncredited, the actor who played Number&nbsp;1 was [[Anthony Dawson]], who had played Professor Dent in the previous Bond film, ''Dr. No'', and appeared in several of Terence Young's films. In the end credits, Blofeld is credited with a [[question mark]]. Blofeld's lines were redubbed by Viennese actor [[Eric Pohlmann]] in the final cut.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> [[Peter Burton]] was unavailable to return as Major Boothroyd, so [[Desmond Llewelyn]], a Welsh actor who was a fan of the [[James Bond (comic strip)|Bond comic strip]] published in the ''[[Daily Express]]'', accepted the part. However, screen credit for Llewelyn was omitted at the opening of the film and is reserved for the exit credits, where he is credited simply as \"Boothroyd\". Llewelyn's character is not referred to by this name in dialogue, but M does introduce him as being from Q Branch. Llewelyn remained as the character, better known as Q, in all but one of the series' films until his death in 1999.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BikCz7XZijEC&pg=PA83|title=The rough guide to James Bond|first=Paul|last=Simpson|page=83|publisher=[[Rough Guides]]|year=2002|accessdate=25 March 2011|isbn=9781843531425}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media |title=Inside Q's Lab |medium=DVD |publisher=[[Metro Goldwyn Mayer|MGM]]/[[United Artists|UA]] Home Entertainment Inc |location=''On Her Majesty's Secret Service'' Ultimate Edition, Disk 2}}</ref>\n\nSeveral actresses were considered for the role of Tatiana, including Italians [[Sylva Koscina]] and [[Virna Lisi]], Danish actress [[Annette Stroyberg|Annette Vadim]], and English-born [[Tania Mallet]].<ref name=\"inside-frwl\">{{Cite AV media |title=Inside From Russia with Love |medium=DVD |publisher=[[Metro Goldwyn Mayer|MGM]]/[[United Artists|UA]] Home Entertainment Inc |year=2000}}</ref> [[Miss Universe 1960|1960]] [[Miss Universe]] runner-up Daniela Bianchi was ultimately cast, supposedly Sean Connery's choice. Bianchi started taking English classes for the role, but the producers ultimately chose to have her lines redubbed by British stage actress [[Barbara Jefford]] in the final cut.<ref name=\"commentary\">''From Russia with Love'' [[audio commentary]], Ultimate Edition DVD</ref> The scene in which Bond finds Tatiana in his hotel bed was used for Bianchi's [[screen test]], with Dawson standing in, this time, as Bond.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> The scene later became the traditional screen test scene for prospective James Bond actors and Bond Girls.<ref>{{Cite AV media |year=2000 | title = Inside Octopussy | medium = DVD | publisher = MGM Home Entertainment Inc. |accessdate =4 August 2007 | url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0322765/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media |year=2000 |title= Inside The Living Daylights |medium= DVD | publisher= MGM Home Entertainment Inc. |accessdate =4 August 2007 | url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0307015/}}</ref> In her initial scene with Klebb, Tatiana refers to training for the ballet, referencing the actress's real life background.\n\nGreek actress [[Katina Paxinou]] was originally considered for the role of Rosa Klebb, but was unavailable. Terence Young cast Austrian singer Lotte Lenya after hearing one of her musical recordings. Young wanted Kronsteen's portrayer to be \"an actor with a remarkable face\", so the minor character would be well remembered by audiences. This led to the casting of [[Vladek Sheybal]], whom Young also considered convincing as an intellectual.<ref name=\"young\">{{Cite AV media |author=[[Terence Young (director)|Terence Young]] |title=From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]] |location=''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1 |publisher= MGM Home Entertainment |id= Accessed 17 October 2008}}</ref> Several women were tested for the roles of Vida and Zora, the two fighting Gypsy girls, and after [[Aliza Gur]] and [[Martine Beswick]] were cast, they spent six weeks practising their fight choreography with stunt work arranger Peter Perkins.<ref>{{Cite AV media |author=[[Aliza Gur]] |title= From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]] |location= ''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1 |publisher = MGM Home Entertainment |id= Accessed 20 October 2008}}</ref> Beswick was mis-credited as 'Martin Beswick' in the film's opening titles, but this error was fixed for the 2001 DVD release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.007museum.com/from_russia_with_love.htm|title=From Russia with Love|website=www.007museum.com}}</ref>\n\nMexican actor [[Pedro Armend\u00e1riz]] was recommended to Young by director [[John Ford]] to play Kerim Bey. After experiencing increasing discomfort on location in Istanbul, Armend\u00e1riz was diagnosed with inoperable cancer. Filming in Istanbul was terminated, the production moved to Britain, and Armend\u00e1riz's scenes were brought forward so that he could complete his scenes without delay. Though visibly in pain, he continued working as long as possible. When he could no longer work, he returned home and took his own life.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\" /> Remaining shots after Armend\u00e1riz left London had a [[stunt double]] and Terence Young himself as stand-ins.<ref name=\"booklet\" />\n\nEnglishman [[Joe Robinson (actor)|Joe Robinson]] was a strong contender for the role of [[Red Grant]] but it was given to Robert Shaw.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thevisitor.co.uk/news/morecambe-and-district-news/joe_has_eye_of_the_tiger_1_1217122|title=Joe has eye of the Tiger |date=10 August 2004 |work= [[The Visitor (Morecambe newspaper)|The Visitor]]}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\n{{See also|List of James Bond vehicles|List of James Bond gadgets|James Bond locations}}\nMost of the film was set in Istanbul, Turkey. Locations included the [[Basilica Cistern]], Hagia Sophia and the [[\u0130stanbul Sirkeci Terminal|Sirkeci railway station]], which also was used for the [[Belgrade]] and [[Zagreb]] railway stations. The MI6 office in London, SPECTRE Island, the Venice hotel and the interior scenes of the Orient Express were filmed at [[Pinewood Studios]] with some footage of the train. In the film, the train journey was set in [[Eastern Europe]]. The journey and the truck ride were shot in [[Argyll]], Scotland and [[Switzerland]]. The end scenes for the film were shot in [[Venice]].<ref name=\"insideFRWL\">{{Cite AV media |year=2000 |title= Inside From Russia with Love |medium = DVD |publisher = MGM Home Entertainment Inc. |people = Martine Beswick, Daniela Bianchi, Dana Broccoli, Syd Cain, Sean Connery, Peter Hunt, John Stears, Norman Wanstall |accessdate =4 August 2007 |url= https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0322760/}}</ref> However, to qualify for the British film funding of the time, at least 70 percent of the film had to have been filmed in Great Britain or the Commonwealth.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Barnes |first1=Alan |last2=Hearn |first2=Marcu |year=1997 |title=Kiss Kiss Bang! Bang!: the Unofficial James Bond Film Companion |publisher= [[Batsford Books]] |isbn= 978-0-7134-8182-2 |page=23}}</ref> The Gypsy camp was also to be filmed in an actual camp in [[Topkap\u0131 Palace|Topkapi]], but was actually shot in a replica of it in Pinewood.<ref name=\"commentary\"/> The scene with rats (after the theft of the Lektor) was shot in Spain, as Britain did not allow filming with wild rats, and an attempt to film white rats painted in cocoa in Turkey did not work.<ref>{{Cite AV media |author=[[Syd Cain]] |title= From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]] |location=''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1|publisher = MGM Home Entertainment |id= Accessed 20 October 2008}}</ref> Principal photography began on 1 April 1963,<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/> and wrapped on 23 August.<ref>{{Cite book |last1=Barnes |first1=Alan |last2=Hearn |first2=Marcu |year=1997 |title=Kiss Kiss Bang! Bang!: the Unofficial James Bond Film Companion |publisher= [[Batsford Books]] |isbn= 978-0-7134-8182-2 |page=24}}</ref> Ian Fleming spent a week in the Istanbul shoot, supervising production and touring the city with the producers.<ref>{{cite book|last=Lycett|first=Andrew|authorlink=Andrew Lycett|title=Ian Fleming|year=1996|publisher=Phoenix|location=London|isbn=978-1-85799-783-5|page=418}}</ref><ref name=hero>{{cite book|title=Some Kind of Hero: The Remarkable Story of the James Bond Films|author1=Field, Matthew |author2=Chowdhury, Ajay |publisher=The History Press|year=2015|isbn=978-0750966504|page=102}}</ref>\n\nDirector Terence Young's eye for realism was evident throughout production. For the opening chess match, Kronsteen wins the game with a reenactment of [[Boris Spassky]]'s victory over [[David Bronstein]] in 1960.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.chessbase.com/newsprint.asp?newsid=1882|title=The name is Spassky \u2013 Boris Spassky |publisher= ChessBase.com |date=2 September 2004 |accessdate=16 February 2008 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121007073815/http://www.chessbase.com/newsprint.asp?newsid=1882 |archivedate=7 October 2012 }}</ref> Production Designer Syd Cain built up the \"chess pawn\" motif in his $150,000 set for the brief sequence.<ref name=\"commentary\"/> Cain also later added a promotion to another movie Eon was producing, making Krilencu's death happen inside a billboard for ''[[Call Me Bwana]]''.<ref name=hero/> A noteworthy gadget featured was the [[attach\u00e9 case]] (briefcase) issued by Q Branch. It had a tear gas bomb that detonated if the case was improperly opened, a folding [[AR-7]] [[sniper rifle]] with twenty rounds of ammunition, a throwing knife, and 50 [[Sovereign (British coin)|gold sovereigns]]. A boxer at [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]], Young choreographed the fight between Grant and Bond along with stunt coordinator Peter Perkins. The scene took three weeks to film and was violent enough to worry some on the production. Robert Shaw and Connery did most of the stunts themselves.<ref name=\"booklet\"/><ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/>\n\nAfter the unexpected loss of Armend\u00e1riz, production proceeded, experiencing complications from uncredited rewrites by [[Berkely Mather]] during filming. Editor [[Peter R. Hunt|Peter Hunt]] set about editing the film while key elements were still to be filmed, helping to restructure the opening scenes. Hunt and Young came up with the idea of moving the Red Grant training sequence to the beginning of the film (prior to the main title), a signature feature that has been an enduring hallmark of every Bond film since. The briefing with Blofeld was rewritten, and back projection was used to refilm Lotte Lenya's lines.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/>\n\nBehind schedule and over-budget, the production crew struggled to complete production in time for the already-announced premiere date that October. On 6 July 1963, while scouting locations in Argyll, Scotland, for that day's filming of the climactic boat chase, Terence Young's helicopter crashed into the water with art director Michael White and a cameraman aboard. The craft sank into 40\u201350 feet (12\u201315&nbsp;m) of water<!-- John Stears -->, but all escaped with minor injuries. Despite the calamity, Young was behind the camera for the full day's work. A few days later, Bianchi's driver fell asleep during the commute to a 6&nbsp;am shoot and crashed the car. The actress's face was bruised and Bianchi's scenes had to be delayed for two weeks while the facial contusions healed.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/>\n\nThe helicopter and boat chase scenes were not in the original novel but were added to create an action climax. The former was inspired by the crop-dusting scene in [[Alfred Hitchcock|Hitchcock's]] ''[[North by Northwest]]'' and the latter by a previous Young/Broccoli/Maibaum collaboration, ''[[The Red Beret]]''.<ref name=\"cork\" /> These two scenes would initially be shot in Istanbul but were moved to Scotland. The speedboats could not go fast enough due to the many waves in the sea,<ref name=\"gotell\"/> and a rented boat filled with cameras ended up sinking in the Bosphorus.<ref name=\"commentary\"/> A helicopter was also hard to obtain, and the special effects crew were nearly arrested trying to get one at a local airbase.<ref name=\"gotell\">{{Cite AV media |author=[[Walter Gotell]] |title=From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]]|location=''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1|publisher = MGM Home Entertainment |id= Accessed 17 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media |author=[[John Stears]] |title=From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]] |location= ''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1 |publisher = MGM Home Entertainment |id= Accessed 17 October 2008}}</ref> The helicopter chase was filmed with a [[radio control]]led miniature helicopter.<ref name=\"commentary\"/> The sounds of the boat chase were replaced in post-production since the boats were not loud enough,<ref>{{Cite AV media |author=Norman Wanstall |title= From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]] |location= ''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1 |publisher = MGM Home Entertainment |id= Accessed 20 October 2008}}</ref> and the explosion, shot in Pinewood, got out of control, burning [[Walter Gotell]]'s eyelids<ref name=\"gotell\" /> and seriously injuring three stuntmen.<ref name=\"cork\">{{Cite AV media |author=John Cork |title= From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]] |location= ''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1 |publisher = MGM Home Entertainment |id= Accessed 20 October 2008}}</ref>\n\nPhotographer [[David Hurn]] was commissioned by the producers of the [[James Bond]] films to shoot a series of stills with [[Sean Connery]] and the actresses of the film. When the [[theatrical property]] [[Walther PPK]] pistol did not arrive, Hurn volunteered the use of his own Walther LP-53 [[air pistol]].<ref>\"http://christies.com/LotFinder/lot_details.aspx?from=searchresults&intObjectID=1992033</ref> Though the photographs of the \"James Bond is Back\" posters of the US release airbrushed out the long barrel of the pistol, [[film poster]] artist Renato Fratini used the long-barrelled pistol for his drawings of Connery on the British posters.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bfi.org.uk/filmtvinfo/library/eventsexh/past/2007_01_10_bond.html|title=Poster Galore |publisher= [[British Film Institute]]|date=10 January 2007 |accessdate=8 February 2011 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120309163839/http://www.bfi.org.uk/filmtvinfo/library/eventsexh/past/2007_01_10_bond.html |archivedate=9 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nFor the opening credits, Maurice Binder had disagreements with the producers and did not want to return.<ref>''[[Starlog (magazine)|Starlog]]'' magazine Maurice Binder interview Part 1</ref> Designer Robert Brownjohn stepped into his place, and projected the credits on female dancers, inspired by [[Constructivism (art)|constructivist]] artist [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Moholy-Nagy]] projecting light onto clouds in the 1920s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.designmuseum.org/design/robert-brownjohn |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-07-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110623223840/http://designmuseum.org/design/robert-brownjohn |archivedate=23 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> Brownjohn's work started the tradition of scantily clad women in the Bond films' title sequences.<ref name=growup>{{cite book |title= \"Grow Up, 007!\" \u2013 James Bond Over the Decades: Formula Vs. Innovation |first=Kerstin |last=J\u00fctting |publisher= GRIN Verlag |year=2007 |isbn= 978-3-638-85372-9|page=13 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=MzuVat9N7bQC&pg=PA12}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{See also|From Russia with Love (soundtrack)}}\n\n''From Russia with Love'' is the first Bond film in the series with John Barry as the primary soundtrack composer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://restless.rimspace.net/soundtrack/fff/from_russia_with_love.htm|title=\"From Russia with Love\" (1963) at Soundtrack Incomplete|accessdate=28 July 2007|publisher=Loki Carbis|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070816071109/http://restless.rimspace.net/soundtrack/fff/from_russia_with_love.htm |archivedate = 16 August 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The theme song was composed by [[Lionel Bart]] of ''[[Oliver!]]'' fame and sung by [[Matt Monro]],<ref name=\"James Bond Theme\">{{cite web|url=http://www.listology.com/content_show.cfm/content_id.10101|title=Listology: Rating the James Bond Theme Songs|accessdate=28 July 2007|publisher=Listology.com}}</ref> although the title credit music is a lively instrumental version of the tune beginning with Barry's brief \"James Bond Is Back\" then segueing into [[Monty Norman]]'s \"[[James Bond Theme]]\". Monro's vocal version is later played during the film (as source music on a radio) and properly over the film's end titles.<ref name=\"James Bond Theme\" /> Barry travelled with the crew to Turkey to try getting influences of the local music, but ended up using almost nothing, just local instruments such as [[Zill|finger cymbals]] to give an exotic feeling, since he thought the Turkish music had a comedic tone that did not fit in the \"dramatic feeling\" of the James Bond movies.<ref name=\"barry\">{{Cite AV media|author=[[John Barry (composer)|John Barry]]|title=From Russia with Love [[audio commentary]]|location=''From Russia with Love'' Ultimate Edition, Disc 1|publisher = MGM Home Entertainment }}</ref>\n\nRecalling his visit to Istanbul, John Barry said, \"It was like no place I'd ever been in my life. [The Trip] was supposedly to seep up the music, so Noel Rogers and I used to go 'round to these nightclubs and listen to all this stuff. We had the strangest week, and really came away with nothing, except a lot of ridiculous stories. We went back, talked to Lionel, and then he wrote 'From Russia with Love.<nowiki>'''</nowiki><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Music_of_James_Bond.html?id=wQE2RmHrErcC|title=The Music of James Bond|last=Burlingame|first=Jon|date=2012-11-01|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199986767|location=|pages=25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn this film, Barry introduced the percussive theme \"[[007 Theme|007]]\"\u2014action music that came to be considered the \"secondary James Bond theme\". He composed it to have a lighter, enthusiastic and more adventurous theme to relax the audience.<ref name=\"barry\"/> The arrangement appears twice on the soundtrack album; the second version, entitled \"007 Takes the Lektor\", is the one used during the gunfight at the Gypsy camp and also during Bond's theft of the Lektor decoding machine.<ref name=\"insideFRWL\"/><ref name=\"music\">{{Cite AV media |year=2000 | title = The Music of James Bond | medium = DVD | publisher = MGM Home Entertainment Inc. |accessdate =4 August 2007 | url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0307198/}}</ref> The completed film features a holdover from the Monty Norman-supervised ''Dr. No'' music; the post-rocket-launch music from ''Dr. No'' is played in ''From Russia with Love'' during the helicopter and speedboat attacks.<ref name=\"music\"/>\n\n==Release and reception==\n''From Russia with Love'' premiered on 10 October 1963 at the [[Odeon Leicester Square]] in London.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Premium for Bond-Lovers:\"From Russia with Love\"|newspaper=[[The Illustrated London News]]|date=5 October 1963|location=London|page=527}}</ref> Ian Fleming, Sean Connery and Walter Gotell attended the premiere. The following year, it was released in 16 countries worldwide, with the United States premiere on 8 April 1964, at New York's [[Astor Theatre, New York City|Astor Theatre]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Sean Connery: a celebration|first=Robert|last=Sellers|publisher=Robert Hale|year=1999|isbn=978-0-7090-6125-0|page=66}}</ref> Upon its first release, ''From Russia with Love'' doubled ''Dr. No''{{'}}s gross by earning $12.5 million (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|12.5|1964}}}} million in {{Inflation-year|US}} dollars{{inflation-fn|US|df=yes}}) at the worldwide box office.<ref>{{cite book|title=United Artists, Volume 2, 1951\u20131978: The Company That Changed the Film Industry|first=Tino|last=Balio|publisher=[[University of Wisconsin Press]]|year=2009|isbn=978-0-299-23014-2|page=261|quote=The picture grossed twice as much as ''Dr. No'', both foreign and domestic \u2013 $12.5 million worldwide}}</ref> After reissue it grossed $78 million,<ref name=\"NumbersBO\">{{cite web|url=http://the-numbers.com/movies/1964/0FRLW.php|title=From Russia with Love|work=The Numbers|publisher=Nash Information Service|accessdate=16 March 2008}}</ref> of which $24 million was from North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=fromrussiawithlove.htm|title=From Russia, with Love (1964)|accessdate=28 July 2007|publisher=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref> It was the most popular movie at the British box office in 1963.<ref>{{cite news|title=Most Popular Films of 1963|newspaper=[[The Times]]|date=3 January 1964|location=London|page=4}}</ref>\n\nThe film's cinematographer [[Ted Moore]] won the [[BAFTA]] award and the [[British Society of Cinematographers]] award for Best Cinematography.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.yahoo.com/movie/1800068321/awards|title=Awards at Yahoo Movies|accessdate=30 July 2007}}</ref> At the 1965 Laurel Awards, Lotte Lenya stood third for Best Female Supporting Performance, and the film secured second place in the Action-Drama category. The film was also nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song]] for \"[[From Russia with Love (soundtrack)|From Russia with Love]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0057076/awards|title=Awards won by From Russia with Love|publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]] | accessdate=1 August 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Contemporary reviews===\nIn comparing the film to its predecessor, ''Dr. No'', [[Richard Roud]], writing in ''[[The Guardian]]'', said that ''From Russia with Love'' \"didn't seem quite so lively, quite so fresh, or quite so rhythmically fast-moving.\"<ref name=\"Roud (1963)\">{{cite news|last=Roud|first=Richard|title=New Films|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 October 1963|authorlink=Richard Roud|location=London|page=11}}</ref> He went on to say that \"...&nbsp;the film is highly immoral in every imaginable way; it is neither uplifting, instructive nor life-enhancing. Neither is it great film-making. But it sure is fun.\"<ref name=\"Roud (1963)\"/> Writing in ''[[The Observer]]'', [[Penelope Gilliatt]] noted that \"The way the credits are done has the same self-mocking flamboyance as everything else in the picture.\"<ref name=\"Gilliatt (1963)\">{{cite news|last=Gilliatt|first=Penelope|title=Laughing it off with Bond: Films|newspaper=[[The Observer]]|date=13 October 1963|authorlink=Penelope Gilliatt|location=London|page=27}}</ref> Gilliatt went on to say that the film manages \"to keep up its own cracking pace, nearly all the way. The set-pieces are a stunning box of tricks\".<ref name=\"Gilliatt (1963)\"/> The critic for ''[[The Times]]'' wrote of Bond that he is \"the secret ideal of the congenital square, conventional in every particular&nbsp;... except in morality, where he has the courage\u2014and the physical equipment\u2014to do without thinking what most of us feel we might be doing&nbsp;...\"<ref name=\"Times (1963)\">{{cite news|title=Four Just Men Rolled into One|newspaper=[[The Times]]|date=10 October 1963|location=London|page=17}}</ref> The critic thought that overall, \"the nonsense is all very amiable and tongue-in-cheek and will no doubt make a fortune for its devisers\".<ref name=\"Times (1963)\"/>\n\n[[Bosley Crowther]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' said: \"Don't miss it! This is to say, don't miss it if you can still get the least bit of fun out of lurid adventure fiction and pseudo-realistic fantasy. For this mad melodramatization of a desperate adventure of Bond with sinister characters in Istanbul and on the Orient Express is fictional exaggeration on a grand scale and in a dashing style, thoroughly illogical and improbable, but with tongue blithely wedged in cheek.\"<ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1964/04/09/archives/james-bond-travels-the-orient-express.html| title = James Bond Travels the Orient Express | date = 9 April 1964 | accessdate=11 May 2009| last=Crowther |first=Bosley | authorlink=Bosley Crowther|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine called the film \"fast, smart, shrewdly directed and capably performed\"<ref name=\"Time (1964)\">{{cite magazine| url= http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,875772,00.html | title= Once More Unto the Breach | magazine= [[Time (magazine)|Time]] | volume=83 | issue=15 | date=10 April 1964 | accessdate=11 May 2009}}</ref> and commented extensively on the film's humour, saying \"Director Young is a master of the form he ridicules, and in almost every episode he hands the audience shocks as well as yocks. But the yocks are more memorable. They result from slight but sly infractions of the thriller formula. A Russian agent, for instance, does not simply escape through a window; no, he escapes through a window in a brick wall painted with a colossal poster portrait of [[Anita Ekberg]], and as he crawls out of the window, he seems to be crawling out of Anita's mouth. Or again, Bond does not simply train a telescope on the Russian consulate and hope he can read somebody's lips; no, he makes his way laboriously into a gallery beneath the joint, runs a submarine periscope up through the walls, and there, at close range, inspects two important Soviet secrets: the heroine's legs.\"<ref name=\"Time (1964)\"/>\n\n===Reflective reviews=== <!-- do not rename this section without fixing the intro's forward reference -->\n''From Russia with Love'' received generally positive reviews from critics; [[Rotten Tomatoes]] sampled 57 reviewers and judged 95% of the reviews to be positive with a rating of 8/10. Its summary states: \"The second James Bond film, ''From Russia with Love'', is a razor-sharp, briskly-paced Cold War thriller that features several electrifying action scenes.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=From Russia With Love (1963)|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/from_russia_with_love/|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=22 January 2014}}</ref> Many online sites also commonly cite ''From Russia with Love'' as the best Bond film of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://commanderbond.net/2750/cbn-reviews-from-russia-with-love.html|title=CBn Reviews 'From Russia With Love'|last=Zydel|first=Devin|publisher=CBn|accessdate=29 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn his 1986 book, [[Danny Peary]] described ''From Russia with Love'' as \"an excellent, surprisingly tough and gritty James Bond film\" which is \"refreshingly free of the gimmickry that would characterise the later Bond films, and Connery and Bianchi play ''real'' people. We worry about them and hope their relationship will work out&nbsp;... Shaw and Lotte Lenya are splendid villains. Both have exciting, well-choreographed fights with Connery. Actors play it straight, with excellent results.\"<ref>Danny Peary, ''Guide for the Film Fanatic'' (Simon & Schuster, 1986) p.163</ref>\n\nFilm critic [[James Berardinelli]] cited this as his favourite Bond film, writing \"Only ''From Russia with Love'' avoids slipping into the comic book realm of ''Goldfinger'' and its successors while giving us a sampling of the familiar Bond formula (action, gadgets, women, cars, etc.). ''From Russia with Love'' is effectively paced and plotted, features a gallery of detestable rogues (including the ultimate Bond villain, Blofeld), and offers countless thrills\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://preview.reelviews.net/top100/103.html|title=Top 100 Runner Up: From Russia with Love|publisher=Reelviews|author=Berardinelli, James|accessdate=16 March 2008|authorlink=James Berardinelli}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2001 Neil Smith of ''[[BBC]] Films'' called it \"a film that only gets better with age\".<ref>{{cite web| title=From Russia with Love (1963)| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2001/06/19/from_russia_with_love_1963_review.shtml|publisher=BBC| date=19 June 2001 | accessdate=16 March 2008}}</ref> In 2004, ''[[Total Film]]'' magazine named it the ninth-greatest British film of all time, making it the only James Bond film to appear on the list.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3711460.stm |title=Get Carter tops British film poll |accessdate=28 July 2007 |date=3 October 2004 |publisher=BBC News}}</ref> In 2006, Jay Antani of Filmcritic praised the film's \"impressive staging of action scenes\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmcritic.com/misc/emporium.nsf/reviews/From-Russia-with-Love|title=From Russia with Love|last=Antani|first=Jay|publisher=Filmcritic.com|accessdate=16 March 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120214102052/http://www.filmcritic.com/reviews/1963/from-russia-with-love/|archivedate=14 February 2012}}</ref> while [[IGN]] listed it as second-best Bond film ever, behind only ''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/746/746573p4.html|title=James Bond's Top 20|publisher=IGN|date=17 November 2006|accessdate=4 March 2008}}</ref> That same year, ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' put the film at ninth among Bond films, criticising the slow pace.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,1560072_14,00.html|title=Ranking the Bond Films|author=Benjamin Svetkey, Joshua Rich|date=15 November 2006|accessdate=16 March 2008|work=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref> When the \"James Bond Ultimate Collector's Set\" was released in November 2007 by MGM, Norman Wilner of [[MSN]] chose ''From Russia with Love'' as the best Bond film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.sympatico.msn.ca/features/ArticleNormanWilner.aspx?cp-documentid=436189|title=Rating the Spy Game|publisher=[[MSN]]|author=Norman Wilner|accessdate=4 March 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080119210839/http://movies.sympatico.msn.ca/features/ArticleNormanWilner.aspx?cp-documentid=436189|archivedate=19 January 2008}}</ref> Conversely, in his book about the Bond phenomenon, ''The Man With the Golden Touch,'' British author Sinclair McKay states \"I know it is heresy to say so, and that some enthusiasts regard ''From Russia With Love'' as the Holy Grail of Bond, but let's be searingly honest \u2013 some of it is crashingly dull.\"<ref>McKay, Sinclair. ''The Man With the Golden Touch.'' Overlook Press: New York. 2008. Pg. 4</ref>\nIn 2014 ''[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]'' polled several film critics, directors, actors and stunt actors to list their top action films;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/film/best-action-movies|work=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]]|title=The 100 best action movies|accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref> ''From Russia With Love'' was listed at 69.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/film/the-100-best-action-movies-70-61?package_page%3D23379 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-03-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150312133940/http://www.timeout.com/newyork/film/the-100-best-action-movies-70-61?package_page=23379 |archivedate=12 March 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThe [[British Film Institute]]'s [[screenonline]] guide called the film \"one of the series' high points\" and said it \"had advantages not enjoyed by many later Bond films, notably an intelligent script that retained the substance of [[From Russia, with Love (novel)|Ian Fleming's novel]] while toning down the overt Cold War politics (the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] had only occurred the previous year).\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/520462/ |title=From Russia With Love (1963) |author=Michael Brooke |work=[[screenonline]] |publisher=[[British Film Institute]] |accessdate=11 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6gse0OdyO |archivedate=19 April 2016 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 2008, [[Michael G. Wilson]], the current co-producer of the series, stated \"We always start out trying to make another ''From Russia with Love'' and end up with another ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]''.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.askmen.com/entertainment/movie/from-russia-with-love.html|title=From Russia With Love|last=Nusair|first=David|publisher=AskMen|date=1 November 2008| accessdate=28 February 2009}}</ref> Sean Connery,<ref name=\"booklet\"/> Michael G. Wilson, Barbara Broccoli, Timothy Dalton and Daniel Craig also consider this their favourite Bond film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmmonthly.com/paul_fischer_profiles/broccoli_and_wilson_rejuvenate_bond_franchise.html|title=Broccoli and Wilson Rejuvenate Bond Franchise|last=Fischer|first=Paul|publisher=FilmMonthly|accessdate=27 March 2010|year=2008}}</ref> [[Albert Broccoli]] listed it with ''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]'' and ''[[The Spy Who Loved Me (film)|The Spy Who Loved Me]]'' as one of his top three favourites,<ref>{{cite web|author=COLIN M JARMAN |url=http://www.licensetoquote.com/2010/06/in-memory-albert-cubby-broccoli.html |title=IN MEMORY: Albert 'Cubby' Broccoli \u2013 The Mastermind behind the James Bond movies |publisher=Licensetoquote.com |date=27 June 2010 |accessdate=21 September 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713204045/http://www.licensetoquote.com/2010/06/in-memory-albert-cubby-broccoli.html |archivedate=13 July 2011 }}</ref> explaining that he felt \"it was with this film that the Bond style and formula were perfected\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Licence to thrill: a cultural history of the James Bond films|first=James |last=Chapman|publisher=I. B. Tauris|year=2007|isbn=978-1-84511-515-9}}</ref>\n\n==Video game adaptation==\n{{Main|From Russia with Love (video game)}}\nIn 2005, the ''[[From Russia with Love (video game)|From Russia with Love]]'' video game was developed by [[Electronic Arts]] and released on 1 November 2005 in North America. It follows the storyline of the book and film, albeit adding in new scenes, making it more action-oriented. One of the most significant changes to the story is the replacement of the organisation [[SPECTRE]] to OCTOPUS because the name SPECTRE constituted a long-running [[Thunderball (novel)#Controversy|legal dispute]] over the film rights to ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]'' between United Artists/MGM and writer [[Kevin McClory]]. Most of the cast from the film returned in likeness. Connery not only allowed his 1960s likeness as Bond to be used, but the actor, in his 70s, also recorded the character's dialogue, marking a return to the role 22 years after he last played Bond in ''[[Never Say Never Again]]''. Featuring a [[virtual camera system|third-person]] [[Multiplayer video game|multiplayer]] [[deathmatch]] mode, the game depicts several elements of later Bond films, such as the [[Aston Martin DB5]] from ''[[Goldfinger (film)|Goldfinger]]'' (1964) and the rocket belt from ''[[Thunderball (film)|Thunderball]]'' (1965).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cube.gamespy.com/gamecube/james-bond-007-from-russia-with-love/654415p1.html|title=Interview with David Carson|publisher=[[GameSpy]]|date=29 September 2005|access-date=8 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/xbox/action/fromrussiawithlove/review.html|title=From Russia With Love Review|last=Navarro|first=Alex|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|date=1 November 2005|access-date=8 February 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130324041325/http://www.gamespot.com/from-russia-with-love/reviews/from-russia-with-love-review-6137026/|archivedate=24 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe game was penned by [[Bruce Feirstein]], who had previously worked on the film scripts for ''[[GoldenEye]]'', ''[[Tomorrow Never Dies]]'', ''[[The World Is Not Enough]]'', and the 2004 video game, ''[[James Bond 007: Everything or Nothing|Everything or Nothing]]''. Its soundtrack was composed by [[Christopher Lennertz]] and [[Vic Flick]].<ref>{{Cite video game|title = [[From Russia with Love (video game)|From Russia with Love]]|developer = [[Electronic Arts]]| date =1 November 2005}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portalbar|1960s|Film|United Kingdom}}\n* [[Outline of James Bond]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=N}}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Peary |first=Danny |authorlink=Danny Peary |title=Cult Movie Stars |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KHhZAAAAMAAJ |year=1991 |publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]] |location=New York |isbn=978-0-671-74924-8 |ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite book |last=Rubin |first=Steven Jay |title=The Complete James Bond Movie Encyclopedia |year=2003 |publisher=[[McGraw-Hill|Contemporary Books]] |location=New York |isbn=978-0-07-141246-9 |ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/dvdsavant/s2065russjump2.html |title=Jump Cut 3: The British Censorship of From Russia with Love from research by Gavin Salkeld |last1=Erickson |first1=Glenn |date=22 July 2006 |publisher=DVDTalk.com |accessdate=30 June 2013}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|From Russia with Love (film)}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.webcitation.org/6gse0OdyO?url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/520462/ ''From Russia With Love''] at [[BFI Screenonline]]\n* {{IMDb title|0057076|From Russia with Love}}\n* {{tcmdb title|75744|From Russia with Love}}\n* {{Amg movie|18751|From Russia with Love}}\n* {{AFI film|id=22487|title=From Russia with Love}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|from_russia_with_love|From Russia with Love}}\n* {{mojo title|fromrussiawithlove|From Russia with Love}}\n* [http://www.mgm.com/title_title.do?title_star=FROMRUSS From Russia With Love] from [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]]\n\n{{James Bond films}}\n{{JB SMERSH stories}}\n{{SPECTRE stories}}\n{{Terence Young}}\n{{Harry Saltzman|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:From Russia With Love (Film)}}\n[[Category:1960s action films]]\n[[Category:1960s spy films]]\n[[Category:1960s thriller films]]\n[[Category:1960s sequel films]]\n[[Category:1963 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American sequel films]]\n[[Category:American spy films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British sequel films]]\n[[Category:British spy films]]\n[[Category:Cold War espionage]]\n[[Category:Cold War spy films]]\n[[Category:Defection in fiction]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Barry (composer)]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Terence Young]]\n[[Category:Films set in Istanbul]]\n[[Category:Films set in L